{In this game, we start examining the King's Indian type of closed centre that
often arises in Queen's Indian Defence.} 1. c4 ({The common move order is} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 {when we reach the position
from the game.}) 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Be7 6. Nc3 O-O
7. d4 {In this position, White has two positional threats - 8.d5 and 8.Qc2
with the idea of playing e2-e4. The typical way of fighting against these
threats is} Ne4 ({The structure arising after} 7... d5 8. cxd5 exd5 {is
favourable for White when Black had already committed his bishop to b7. The
problem is that due to the pressure on the c-file, sooner or later, Black will
be forced to play ...c7-c5. In this case, White will decide when to get a
favourable version of the hanging pawns. The following sample line is quite
illustrative:} 9. b3 Nbd7 10. Bb2 Re8 11. Rc1 c5 12. e3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4] As
a rule, the central tension is favourable for the side that can potentially
release it in a favourable way. In this concrete case, it's obvious that Black
cannot release the tension by means of ...cxd4 since he will get a horrible
version of IQP. On the other hand, having a bishop on g2, White can always
consider the transition into a position with hanging pawns by playing dxc5. Of
course, he is not in a rush. Beforehand, he can play various improving moves.
For instance, the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-f4 always comes into consideration in such
positions.}) ({Challenging the centre with} 7... c5 $2 {is just bad. After} 8.
d5 exd5 9. cxd5 $16 {Black gets a terrible Benoni structure due to the awkward
position of his bishops.}) 8. Qc2 {This is by far White's most popular choice
in this position. As we are going to see on many occasions, in Queen's Indian
Defence, the fight often revolves around the e4-square.} Nxc3 {In my opinion,
this is the simplest reaction. This option is also very practical since Black
can play this position mainly by relying on his understanding.} 9. Qxc3 d6 10.
Qc2 {An important moment. White is preparing the thematic advance e2-e4.
Therefore, Black should immediately prevent this idea by means of} f5 {This
move should be considered whenever White is ready to play e2-e4. Had White
played 10.Qd3, our reaction would have been the same.} 11. d5 {This move leads
to a KID of closed centre. This will be the first important structure we are
going to deal with. Obviously, Black should play} e5 {In my opinion, this
King's Indian structure is very decent for Black. Compared to the usual KID
positions, Black's only disadvantage is the b7-bishop. In closed positions,
when tempis are not so important, we can easily waste time on ...Bc8, thus
improving the bishop. Having played d4-d5, however, White provides the
c5-square to the black knight. Therefore, Black almost automatically plays ...
Nd7, ...a7-a5, and ...Nc5. Also, having quickly played ...f7-f5, Black enjoys
a superior central control. Therefore, White usually tries to challenge the
centre.} ({A terrible positional mistake would be} 11... exd5 $4 12. Nd4 Qd7
13. cxd5 $18 {[%csl Rc7,Re6] when White immediately achieves a strategically
winning position.}) 12. e4 Bc8 {Remember this thematic move. The bishop should
be improved as soon as possible.} 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Qe2 Nd7 {It's very
important to understand how to handle this thematic structure. It's obvious
that White's queenside play based on the advance c4-c5 is unrealistic. That's
why, White often goes for an alternative idea - pushing f2-f4 after bringing
the knight to e4. In this structure, Black usually tries to exchange the minor
pieces. Especially, he should prioritize the trade of the dark-squared bishops.
Positions with only heavy pieces on the board are slightly better for Black.
The reason is that Black has the semi-open f-file at his disposal. If White
goes for a passive play, Black's standard way of developing the advantage
includes the following moves: ...a7-a5, ...Nc5, ...Qe8-g6, ...Rf7, and Raf8.}
15. Nd2 Bg5 $1 {Always play this key move when you have the possibility. In
this way, Black practically forces the exchange of the dark-squared bishops.
The next few moves are thematic for the structure.} 16. Ne4 Bxc1 17. Raxc1 a5
18. Qe3 Qe8 {[%cal Ge8g6] The queen is heading to its best spot in this
structure - the g6-square.} 19. b3 Qg6 20. Rfe1 h6 $1 {Another important move.
Before doubling his rooks on the f-file, Black rules out any Ng5 ideas. It's
clear that White does not have constructive ideas. He should just sit and wait.
} 21. Rcd1 Rf7 22. Rd2 Raf8 {[%cal Gg6h5,Gf5h3] Black is ready to launch a
kingside attack. Larsen is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops by
means of ...Qh5 followed by ...Bh3. After such an exchange, White will face
difficulties covering the weak light squares around the king.} 23. Qc3 Qh5 24.
Qe3 Bh3 25. Qc3 g5 {Gaining space on the kingside is obviously useful.} ({
Nevertheless, even more logical would have been} 25... Nf6 {As I have already
pointed out, exchanging the minor pieces is Black's main strategic goal in
this pawn structure. Later on, Larsen does it.}) 26. Bh1 Qg6 27. Qe3 Bg4 {
Black is going to exchange the bishops via f3.} 28. Qc3 Bf3 29. Bxf3 Rxf3 30.
Rd3 R3f5 $1 {Black should definitely refrain from exchanging heavy pieces in
this structure. White's rooks do not have any perspectives.} 31. Rd2 h5 {
Once again, the immediate ...Nf6 would have been completely possible. Larsen,
however, prefers to strengthen his kingside position to the maximum.} 32. Qd3
g4 33. Re3 Kg7 34. Kg2 Nf6 {Finally, Black forces the transition into an
endgame with heavy pieces. Black's activity combined with the vulnerable
White's kingside make Black's position winning.} 35. Nxf6 R8xf6 ({Even more
precise would have been} 35... Qxf6 {when after} 36. Ree2 h4 37. Qe4 Qg6 {
[%cal Gf5f2]} 38. Kg1 hxg3 39. hxg3 Qh5 $19 {Black is winning due to the
lethal threats on the h-file.}) 36. Qe4 Qg5 37. Rde2 h4 38. Kg1 Rf3 39. Rc2 ({
Exchanging the rooks with} 39. Rxf3 $2 {does not work tactically. The problem
is that after} gxf3 40. Re3 Rf4 41. Qc2 Qg4 {[%cal Gg4h3]} 42. Qd1 Rd4 43. Qf1
Qf5 {[%cal Gf5c2] Black pieces penetrate White's position. Black is already
planning ... Qc2 on the next move.}) 39... Qh5 $6 {This is an inaccuracy.
Nevertheless, after a few slight mistakes by White, Larsen managed to win the
game.} ({After} 39... hxg3 40. hxg3 Rxe3 41. Qxe3 Qxe3 42. fxe3 Rf3 $19 {
Black is easily winning in the rook endgame.}) 40. Re1 hxg3 41. fxg3 Qh3 42.
Rg2 Kf8 43. Rb1 Ke7 44. Re1 Kd8 45. Rb1 Qh5 46. Rc2 Ke7 47. Re1 Rf8 48. Rd2 Qf7
49. Qe2 Qf5 50. Rb2 Rf6 51. Rc2 Kf7 52. Rd2 e4 53. Rdd1 0-1

