{The following game is a real masterpiece when it comes to handling positions
with a closed centre in Queen's Indian Defence. Once again, the main tabiya
was reached via the Reti move order -} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7
5. O-O Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. d4 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. Qd3 {This is the
alternative way of preparing e2-e4. In comparison to 10.Qc2, this time White
is ready to answer ...f7-f5 with Qe3. That's what actually happened in the
game -} f5 11. Qe3 {Now, Black should decide how to defend the e6-pawn.} ({
Another typical reaction to ...f7-f5 is} 11. Ne1 Bxg2 12. Nxg2 {[%cal Ge2e4]
White is now ready to execute the thematic e2-e4 advance. Via the f4-square,
the knight can put additional pressure on e6. In my opinion, Black's most
precise continuation is} Qd7 $1 {By protecting the e6-pawn in advance, Black
is ready to answer} 13. e4 fxe4 14. Qxe4 {with} d5 {Remember this key idea. In
case of} 15. Qe2 Nc6 $132 {Black already starts putting pressure on d4. Later
on, we are going to take a detailed look at such positions.}) 11... Qc8 {
The queen is forced to this passive square. On the other hand, the white queen
is also not optimally placed.} ({Unfortunately, the usually desirable} 11...
Qd7 $6 {is well met by} 12. Ne5 Qc8 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Nd3 {when Black faces
some difficulties due to the vulnerable e6-pawn.}) 12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 {
Once again, White is planning to mount the pressure by means of Nf4. Therefore,
Black must play energetically.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Besides putting pressure on
d4, Black is ready to expand in the centre with ...e6-e5. Therefore, White's
thematic reaction is} 14. d5 {when after} Nd8 {the game can take two different
directions. In the game, Fridman to allow ...e6-e5 by playing} 15. Qd3 ({
Generally speaking, the structure arising after} 15. dxe6 Nxe6 {is considered
to be favourable for White due to the control of the d5-square. If White
manages to establish a knight on d5, Black will need to either exchange it or
chase it away with ...c7-c6. In both cases, a backward pawn will appear in
Black's camp. These are, however, static considerations. When we take a look
at the dynamic factors, the picture is completely different. First of all, two
pairs of minor pieces have already been exchanged. Therefore, White's space
advantage is no longer significant. Additionally, besides being behind in
development, White has to waste time on improving his awkwardly placed pieces.
The weakened light squares around the light king are another important factor.
In many cases, Black can initiate kingside activity by means of ...f5-f4. The
following sample lines, illustrate the nature of this position.} 16. Qd3 Bf6
17. Rb1 {White is preparing the development of the bishop.} ({The attempt to
establish a knight on d5 by means of} 17. Ne3 {is well met by} f4 $132) 17...
Be5 18. e3 Nc5 19. Qc2 a5 $132 {[%cal Gc8e8,Ge8h5] Black is doing fine. White
should already reckon with the idea of ...Qe8-h5.}) 15... Bf6 {Black is trying
to hinder White's queenside development.} ({I would have played the immediate} 
15... e5 $1) 16. Rb1 a5 17. b3 e5 {Finally, we reach the thematic pawn
structure with a closed centre.} 18. e4 fxe4 19. Qxe4 {In comparison to the
previous game, White's position is even worse. The white knight is far away
from the e4-square. As we know, the queen is a very bad piece for a blockade.}
Qh3 {Atalik immediately seizes the opportunity to activate his queen.} 20. Ne1
Nf7 {[%cal Gf6g5] Black is already planning to execute the thematic exchange
of the dark-squared bishops. If allowed, he will follow with ...Bg5.} 21. Nf3
h6 $1 {[%cal Gf7g5] A very strong positional move. Black is going to exchange
the minor pieces via the g5-square.} 22. Bd2 Ng5 $1 23. Bxg5 Bxg5 {[%cal Gf8f7,
Ga8f8]} 24. Rbe1 {Of course, White does not want to give his knight for the
g5-bishop. Black, however, can challenge the knight's stability by doubling
the rooks on the f-file.} Rf7 25. Re2 Raf8 26. Ne1 {Now, the white king is
left without defenders. Therefore, the advance ...h6-h5-h4 comes into
consideration. Before that, Atalik decides to open a file on the queenside by
means of} a4 ({Of course, there is nothing wrong with} 26... h5 {when after}
27. f3 {Black can play} Bc1 {[%cal Gc1a3,Ga3c5] with the idea of transferring
the bishop to c5.} ({Also, after} 27... h4 28. Qg6 Bh6 $15 {Black is better.}))
27. f3 axb3 28. axb3 Ra8 {This is the idea behind ...a5-a4. Now, Black is
playing on the entire board.} 29. Nc2 h5 30. Rg2 h4 31. f4 Raf8 32. Ne3 $2 {
A blunder in a very difficult position.} exf4 33. Qe6 fxg3 $1 {This is the
point. White cannot take the queen because of the mate.} 34. Rxf7 Bxe3+ 35.
Qxe3 Rxf7 36. hxg3 hxg3 37. Qe1 Rf3 38. Ra2 Kf7 39. Re2 Re3 0-1

