{ The following fragment taken from the practice of Kramnik shows a
typical structural transformation that might arise in closed QID structures.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2
Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. Qc2 f5 11. d5 e5 12. e4 Bc8 13. Qe2 {Contrary to the game
of Larsen, White is not in a hurry to release the central tension by playing
exf5. Kramnik played} Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5] with the idea of bringing the knight
to c5. The critical position arises after} 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Nd2 Nc5 16. Ne4 {
It's obvious that White didn't manage to get anything out of the opening since
Black can already decide how exactly to exchange all the minor pieces. The
question is whether to go for immediate exchanges or allow White to take on c5.
Kramnik went for the second option -} a5 {Black does not mind Nxc5 and makes a
typical move designed to improve the queenside structure.} ({It goes without
saying that after the thematic exchange operation} 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18.
Qxe4 Bg5 $11 {Black is at the better side of the equality.}) {Kramnik played
16...a5 because he knows that the structure arising after} 17. Nxc5 bxc5 {
[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga5a4,Ga8b8] is good for Black. In almost all cases, Black
should welcome this structural transformation. Besides getting better central
control, Black can already consider playing on the b-file. Fixing the b2-pawn
by means of ...a5-a4 in combination with ...Rb8 tends to be pretty annoying
for White.} 18. Bd2 a4 19. Be4 g6 {In my opinion, this move is an inaccuracy.}
({Better would have been} 19... Bg5 {when after} 20. Bxf5 Rxf5 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 {
[%csl Rg1][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Ga8f8] Black gets his typical edge in an endgame
with heavy pieces. A possible continuation would be ...Raf8 followed by the
march of the h-pawn. Black can combine his kingside attack with pressure on
the b-file.}) {After the game continuation, White got enough time to play} 20.
b4 {After} axb3 21. axb3 Rb8 22. Rab1 Bg5 23. Bxf5 gxf5 24. f4 exf4 25. Bxf4
Qf6 $11 {The position was equal. Despite his tries, Kramnik didn't manage to
win.} 26. Bxg5 Qxg5 27. Rf4 Rbe8 28. Qd3 Re5 29. Rbf1 h5 30. Kg2 Kg7 31. R1f2
Kg6 32. R2f3 Ra8 33. Rf2 Rf8 34. h4 Qf6 35. Qc2 Kg7 36. Qd3 Qg6 37. Qc3 Kh7 38.
Qd3 Kg8 39. Qf3 Qe8 40. Qd1 Rf6 41. Qc2 Kg7 42. Kh2 Rf7 43. Qb2 Kg6 44. b4 cxb4
45. Qxb4 Re2 46. Qb1 Re1 47. Qc2 Qe5 48. Kg2 Re3 49. Kh2 Re4 50. Qd2 Kg7 51.
Qd1 Kg6 52. Qd2 Rf6 53. Qa5 Qe7 54. Qd2 Rf7 55. Qc1 Qe5 1/2-1/2

