{As I have mentioned on several occasions, in Queen's Indian Defence, the
fight usually revolves around the e4-square. In this high-profile game, we
shall see some typical ideas that both sides can use in the battle for this
key central square.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. b3 Nd7 {This is the main move in the
position.} ({In the previous game, we have examined} 10... f5) 11. Bb2 Be4 {
A very typical move for Queen's Indian Defence. First of all, Black physically
blocks the e-pawn. At the same time, White cannot prepare this advance by
means of Qc2 and Qd3. Additionally, there is another point behind this
bishop's move. In many cases, Black attacks the centre with ...c7-c5. White
often answers this advance with d4-d5. In such a case, it's better for Black
to have a bishop on e4 rather than b7.} ({A typical mistake would be} 11... f5
$2 {when after} 12. Ng5 Bxg5 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bc6 $16 {[%cal Gb3b4,Ga2a4,Ga4a5]
White enjoys a big advantage. He is going to proceed with b3-b4 followed by
a2-a4-a5.}) 12. Bh3 $1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Ge2e4] This time, White uses a typical
device in the fight for the e4-square. The idea is Nd2 followed by e2-e4. At
the same time, he prevents Black from exchanging the light-squared bishops.} ({
Not so challenging is} 12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 {when the simplest solution for
Black is} c5 {As a rule, when White is ready to play e2-e4, we should find a
way to attack the centre.} 14. d5 {This move leads to a Benoni structure. If
Black allows ...cxd4, then we will get a typical QID Hedgehog structure.} Bf6
15. Qd2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 exd5 17. cxd5 Re8 {Compared to the usual Benoni
positions, due to the massive piece exchanges, White's space advantage is not
a significant factor. Additionally, Black can easily deliver the thematic ...
b6-b5 break. Later on, we will take a detailed look at the Benoni structures.})
12... Bf6 {In my opinion, this is not the most precise reaction.} ({Whenever
White is preparing e2-e4, I prefer the immediate attack in the centre.
Therefore, more to the point would have been} 12... c5 $1 13. Rfd1 Rc8 14. Rac1
({Nothing gives} 14. dxc5 Bf6 15. Qc1 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Bxf3 17. exf3 dxc5 $11 {
when Black gets at least an equal position.}) 14... h6 {Black can make useful
waiting moves until White clarifies his intentions.} 15. Qe3 Bb7 16. d5 {
Once again, White goes for a Benoni structure. After} exd5 17. cxd5 Rc7 18. Qd3
Bf6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 $132 {Black has a decent counterplay.}) 13. Rad1 Qe7 14. Rd2
$1 {[%cal Gc3e3] White is planning Qe3 followed by d4-d5. With his last move,
besides protecting the b2-bishop, he is also preparing to double the rooks on
the d-file.} a5 ({After} 14... c5 {Giri would have probably played} 15. Qe3 Bb7
16. Rfd1 {with an annoying pressure.}) 15. Qe3 Bb7 16. d5 $1 {This move marks
the beginning of a forced sequence.} Bxb2 17. dxe6 Bf6 18. exd7 Qxe3 19. fxe3
Rad8 20. Nd4 Bxd4 21. exd4 Bc6 22. c5 Bxd7 23. Bxd7 Rxd7 24. cxb6 cxb6 25. Rc1
$14 {The smoke has cleared. It's obvious that Black didn't manage to achieve
full equality. Finally, Eljanov successfully defended this position.} d5 26.
Rc6 Rb8 27. Rdc2 Kf8 28. Kf2 Ke7 29. Kf3 Rd6 30. Rc7+ Ke6 31. a3 Rbd8 32. Kf4
Kf6 33. R2c6 g5+ 34. Kf3 h5 35. b4 axb4 36. axb4 Rxc6 37. Rxc6+ Kf5 38. Rxb6
Ra8 39. Rd6 Ra3+ 40. Kf2 Ke4 41. Rf6 Rb3 42. h4 Kxd4 43. hxg5 Rxb4 44. Rxf7 Ke5
45. Rh7 Kf5 46. Rxh5 Kg6 47. Rh4 d4 48. Kf3 Rb3+ 49. Kf2 Rb4 50. Re4 Kf5 51.
Rf4+ Kxg5 52. Ke1 Rb1+ 53. Kd2 Rg1 54. Rf3 Kg4 55. Rf4+ Kg5 56. Rxd4 Rxg3 57.
Rd3 Rg4 58. Rf3 Ra4 59. Rf8 Kg6 60. Ke3 Ra3+ 61. Kf4 Ra6 62. Rf5 Re6 63. e4 Rf6
1/2-1/2

