{ The Hedgehog is another very important pawn structure
that often arises in Queen's Indian Defence with g2-g3. This structure is
usually reached when Black attacks White's centre by means of ...c7-c5.
Usually, the arising Hedgehog structures are quite decent for Black. The thing
is that the g2-bishop does not control the diagonal f1-a6. Therefore, Black
can easily execute one of the thematic breaks ...b6-b5. The following game is
a good illustration. The critical position arises on move 13.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6
10. b3 Nd7 11. Bb2 Nf6 12. Rad1 Be4 {We already know this typical move. Black
indicates his intention to attack the centre by means of ...c7-c5.} ({The
immediate} 12... c5 {is well met by} 13. d5 {In this case, the b7-bishop will
be very problematic for Black.}) 13. Bh3 {Once again, White uses this typical
way of fighting for the e4-square. After chasing the bishop away, he will
start preparing e2-e4. Therefore, Black immediately strikes in the centre -} c5
{The next few moves are quite logical -} 14. Ng5 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Bg6 16. Bg2 Rc8
{Finally, we got a stable position with the Hedgehog structure. In such
positions, Black has two major ideas at his disposal - ...d6-d5 and ...b6-b5.
Since White has very good control of the d5-square, the second option is more
realistic. Before the Hedgehog structure, always check whether White can
effectively attack the d6-pawn. In the game, Can played} 17. Ne4 {This is the
most ambitious choice. The idea is to obtain the bishop pair.} ({Obviously,
one should always watch for moves like} 17. Ba3 $6 {In this case, however,
White's idea does not work tactically. After} d5 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. cxd5 Nxd5
20. Bxd5 exd5 $15 {[%csl Re2,Rg5][%cal Ge7g5,Ge7e2] It transpires that White
cannot simultaneously cover the g5-knight and the e2-pawn.}) 17... Bxe4 18.
Bxe4 Qc7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc7b8,Ga7a6,Gb6b5] The computer claims a slight
advantage for White, mainly because of the bishop pair and the space advantage.
This is something that you will often witness when analyzing Hedgehog
structures. On the other hand, Black has a clear plan. After ...Rfd8 and ...
Qb8, he will follow with the thematic idea ...a7-a6 and ...b6-b5.} 19. Rd2 Rfd8
20. Rfd1 Qb8 21. Bf3 a6 22. e4 {The computer does not approve this move.} ({
Much more logical would have been} 22. a4 $1 {with the idea to answer} b5 $6
23. cxb5 axb5 24. a5 {[%csl Ga5] when the a-pawn is a very important asset. On
the other hand, Black is not forced to go for the immediate 22...b5. Very
often, when White plays a2-a4 in Hedgehog positions, Black tries to transfer
the knight to c5. In this way, he can make use of the vulnerable queenside.})
22... b5 $1 {Now, this break works really well.} 23. cxb5 axb5 {By deflecting
the c4-pawn, Black manages to reduce White's central control. When possible,
it's advisable to fix White's queenside structure by means of ...b5-b4. In the
game, White decided to force matters with} 24. e5 dxe5 25. Qxe5 Rxd2 26. Rxd2
Qxe5 27. Bxe5 b4 $1 28. Kf1 Kf8 {In this equal position, the draw was agreed.}
1/2-1/2

