{ The next game illustrates a very
typical feature of the Hedgehog structure. White usually face difficulties
finding a constructive plan. Therefore, he mainly tries to prevent Black's
counterplay based on ...d6-d5 or ...b6-b5. Therefore, when playing such
positions, you should be ready to shuffle around with your pieces for a long
time. Patience and readiness to start an immediate counterplay are very
typical for every Hedgehog player.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5.
Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2 {After 8.Qc2, this is White's second most
popular choice in this position. The idea is to answer ...Nxc3 with Bxc3.
Meanwhile, White is getting ready to attack the e4-knight either by playing 9.
Qc2 or 9.Ne5. On the downside, the move 8.Bd2 makes the d4-pawn a bit more
vulnerable. Therefore, Black's most principled reaction is} Bf6 {After} 9. Qc2
Nxd2 10. Qxd2 d6 11. e4 {we reach one of the most typical structures for the
system with 4.g3. White provided his opponent with the bishop pair in order to
build a strong pawn centre. On the other hand, Black's pawn structure is very
flexible. He can challenge the centre either with ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5. The
Hedgehog structure might arise after ...c7-c5 followed by ...cxd4. That's what
happened in this game.} Nd7 12. Rad1 g6 13. h4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 Bg7 15. Qc2 c5 16.
b3 {With this move, Anand shows that he has nothing against playing the
Hedgehog.} cxd4 17. Nxd4 a6 {Finally, the Hedgehog formation has been reached.
Despite his tremendous space advantage, White does not have a concrete plan.
Due to the absence of the dark-squared bishop, the white knights might become
vulnerable at some point. As the advance ...d6-d5 is not realistic, Black will
focus his efforts on executing the break ...b6-b5.} 18. Qd2 Rfd8 19. Qe3 Rab8 {
Indicating the intention to prepare ...b6-b5. Usually, in such positions,
Black tries different positions for his pieces. This is due to the slow
character of the play.} 20. Rd2 Nf6 {[%cal Ge7c7] preparing to put the queen
on c7.} 21. Bf3 Qc7 22. Red1 Nd7 23. Bg2 Rbc8 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb6b5] Pay
attention at this typical Hedgehog move. Black is preparing the advance ...
b6-b5 by making use of the vulnerable c3-knight.} 24. Bh3 {[%cal Gh3e6] By
creating the threat of Bxe6, Anand wants to force the d8-rook into e8. In this
way, the d6-pawn will become vulnerable.} ({Black would very much welcome a
move like} 24. a4 {since after the thematic} Nc5 {White's queenside is getting
vulnerable.}) 24... Re8 25. Nde2 {[%csl Gc3] Covering the c3-knight and
putting pressure on d6.} Bf8 26. h5 Nf6 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Bg2 Ba8 $1 {This
move is very typical for the Hedgehog structures. In this concrete case,
Carlsen is planning to exchange the queens via c5. Since the b7-bishop will
lack protection, Black will need to reckon with the advance e4-e5.
Additionally, very often the move ...Ba8 is played with the idea of ...Rb8
followed by ...b6-b5.} 29. Bf3 {This move shows that Anand cannot find
anything concrete.} Qc5 30. Qxc5 Rxc5 {[%cal Gb6b5] Black is now ready to
deliver ...b6-b5. That's why White started playing dynamically -} 31. Na4 Rc7
32. Nxb6 Bxe4 {Obviously, the central pawn is more important. Black is already
slightly better. Later on, Anand managed to hold his dangerous opponent to a
draw. Since the remaining part of the game is not related to the Hedgehog
structure, I leave it without comments.} 33. Kg2 Rb8 34. Na4 d5 35. cxd5 Bxf3+
36. Kxf3 Nxd5 37. Nf4 Nxf4 38. gxf4 Rb5 39. Nb2 Rf5 40. Nc4 g5 41. Rd4 Kg7 42.
Rg1 Bc5 43. Re4 Kf6 44. Rxg5 Rxg5 45. fxg5+ Kxg5 46. Ne3 Ba7 47. Rc4 Rxc4 48.
Nxc4 Kf6 49. b4 e5 50. a4 Ke6 51. b5 e4+ 52. Kxe4 axb5 53. axb5 Bxf2 54. b6 f5+
55. Kf3 Bxb6 56. Nxb6 f4 57. Nd5 Kxd5 58. Kxf4 1/2-1/2

