{ Sometimes, Black is playing a Hedgehog setup with a pawn on d7,
instead of d6. The following model game of Pavel Eljanov is very illustrative
for such positions.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2 Bf6 9. Ne5 {This move is a logical follow-up of 8.Bd2.
Black's most precise reaction is} Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 c5 {It becomes
clear that if White allows ...cxd4, we will get a Hedgehog structure. In the
game, Hammer played} 12. Ng4 ({The structure arising after} 12. dxc5 bxc5 {
will be dealt with in the next examples.}) 12... Bxd4 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4
Nc6 15. Qd6 {Having a pawn on d7, instead of d6 is often in Black's favour.
First of all, it's easier for Black to defend the d7-pawn. At the same time,
the c6-knight is more stable now. Of course, Black should find a way to
challenge the blockade on the d6-square. The typical way to do it is} Qg5 $1 {
[%cal Gg5c5,Gf8d8] This is the key move in Black's strategy. Eljanov is
planning to proceed with ...Rfd8 followed by ...Qc5. An additional, and even
more aggressive idea is ...Rad8 combined with ...f7-f5.} 16. Ne3 Rfd8 ({
The alternative} 16... Rad8 {[%cal Gf7f5] followed by ...f7-f5 will be dealt
with in the theoretical section.}) 17. Rad1 Qc5 {This is the point of Black's
setups. After exchanging the queens on d6, Black is going to bring his king to
e7. Note that Black is not in a hurry to exchange the queens on d6. If White
exchanges the queens, the structure arising after ...bxc5 is favourable for
Black.} 18. a3 $6 {In my opinion, this move is a slight inaccuracy. Now,
White's queenside structure is less flexible.} a5 $1 {Of course! No one will
allow the advance b2-b4. Furthermore, Black is ready to fix the queenside by
means of ...a5-a4. Therefore, White should play} 19. b3 ({As we will see in
the next examples, after} 19. Qxc5 $2 bxc5 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3][%cal Ga5a4,Ga8b8,
Gb8b2,Gg8f8,Gf8e7,Gd7d6] Black gets a superior pawn structure due to the
increased central control and the pressure along the b-file. If allowed, he
will proceed with ...a5-a4 followed by ...Rab8, thus putting an annoying
pressure on the b-file. Of course, Black will also bring the king to e7.})
19... Rab8 20. a4 $2 {Obviously, this move is a positional mistake. White's
queenside will be now a target. White probably wanted to prevent ...b6-b5 at
any cost. As it usually happens in Hedgehog structures, in response to a3-a4,
Black will transfer his knight all the way to c5.} Nb4 $1 {Black is already
planning to reroute the knight to c5 via a6.} 21. Rd2 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 Kf8 23.
Rfd1 Ke7 {[%cal Gb4a6,Ga6c5] After covering the e7-pawn, Black is ready to
follow with the manoeuvre...Na6-c5.} 24. g4 {This move is designed to prevent
Black from grabbing kingside space by means of ...f7-f5. On the flipside,
Black has now the possibility to initiate kingside play with ...h7-h5.} Na6 25.
R6d3 Nc5 26. Rc3 h5 $1 $17 {A clear illustration of the principle of the two
weaknesses. The vulnerable b3-pawn is not enough for Black to win the game.
Therefore, Eljanov looks for targets on the kingside. I leave the remaining
part of the game without comments since it's not related to our topic. I
strongly advise you, however, to follow the game until the end and to enjoy
the technique of Eljanov.} 27. h3 Rh8 28. f3 Rbc8 29. Nc2 hxg4 30. hxg4 Rh6 31.
Rh1 Rxh1 32. Kxh1 Rc6 33. Kg2 Rd6 34. Kf2 Rd1 35. b4 axb4 36. Nxb4 Ra1 37. Nd3
Rxa4 38. Nxc5 bxc5 39. Ke3 Kd6 40. Rc1 g5 41. Ke4 f6 42. f4 gxf4 43. Kxf4 Ke7
44. Kf3 e5 45. e3 Ke6 46. Rh1 Rxc4 47. Rh6 Rc1 48. Kf2 Rc2+ 49. Kf3 d5 50. g5
e4+ 51. Kg3 Re2 52. Rxf6+ Ke5 0-1

