{[#] The next game of Pavel Eljanov features another Hedgehog position arising
from the same variation. This time, White refrains from exchanging the queens.
The first 17 moves repeat the previous example. Instead of 18.a3 played by
Hammer, Al Sayed went for} 18. Qf4 {After} Ne5 19. Rd2 Qc6+ 20. Kg1 d6 {
we have a classical Hedgehog position. After covering the d6-pawn, Black will
try to prepare the thematic advance ...b6-b5.} 21. Rad1 {[%cal Gf4e5] creating
the threat of Qxe5.} Rd7 22. b3 Rad8 23. Nc2 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5] Already, it's
time to start preparing ...b6-b5.} 24. Nb4 Qb7 25. Qd4 h5 {A very nice
multipurpose move. Besides, creating room for the king, in some cases, Black
is ready to create kingside threats by pushing the pawn all the way to h3.
Additionally, with his last move, Eljanov secures the g4-square for the knight.
} ({Of course, there is nothing wrong with} 25... b5) 26. f4 $2 {As it often
happens in Hedgehog structures, failing to find a constructive plan, White
gets nervous. This is the moment when he starts making concessions. The
advance f2-f4 weakens the kingside as well as the e4-square.} Ng4 27. h3 Nf6
28. Rd3 Ne4 $6 {Such inaccuracies are quite typical for blitz games.} ({
Better would have been} 28... Rc8 {[%cal Gb6b5] with the idea to follow with ..
.b6-b5.}) 29. Qe3 {White misses his chance.} ({He should have played} 29. Nxa6
Qxa6 30. Qxe4 Qxa2 {when the position is unclear.}) 29... b5 30. cxb5 $2 {
After this positional mistake, Black gets an obvious advantage.} ({With no
time on the clock, it's not easy to see the precise} 30. Rd4 Nf6 31. Qf3 Qb6
32. Qc6 {with a decent counterplay.}) 30... axb5 31. Rd4 d5 $17 {Black has a
big advantage due to his superior central control and White's vulnerable king.
Later in the game, Eljanov managed to convert his advantage.} 32. Nd3 Rc8 33.
Nf2 Rc3 34. R4d3 Rxd3 35. Rxd3 Nd6 36. Rc3 b4 37. Rc2 Rc7 38. Qd3 Qb6 39. Rxc7
Qxc7 40. Qd4 Qc3 41. Qxc3 bxc3 42. Nd3 f6 43. a4 c2 44. a5 e5 45. fxe5 fxe5 46.
a6 Nb5 47. Kf2 e4 48. Nc1 d4 49. Ke1 e3 50. Kf1 g5 51. g4 hxg4 52. hxg4 Kf7 53.
Kg2 Ke6 54. Kf3 Ke5 55. b4 Kd5 56. Nd3 Na7 57. Nc1 Kc4 58. Ke4 Kc3 59. Kd5 Kd2
60. Nb3+ Kxe2 61. Kxd4 Kf2 62. Nc1 e2 63. Nd3+ Kf1 64. Kc3 c1=Q+ 0-1

