{ The Benoni type of structures also arise very often in Queen's
Indian Defence. Such a structure arises when Whtie answers ...c7-c5 with d4-d5.
This example features one of White's critical variations against Queen's
Indian -} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. Nc3 Ne4 7. Bd2
Bf6 8. O-O O-O {We are already very well familiar with these moves. In the
previous games, we have been examining White's attempts to put pressure on e4
by playing either 9.Ne5 or 9.Qc2. Another very ambitious move is} 9. Rc1 {
By overprotecting the knight, White is getting ready to answer} c5 {with} 10.
d5 {The inclusion of 9.Rc1 prevents Black from spoiling White's structure by
exchanging the c3-knight. The first important position is being reached after}
exd5 11. cxd5 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 d6 {Finally, we have reached a typical Benoni
structure. The fact that one pair of minor pieces has already been exchanged
is in Black's favour. When we have less space, we should try to exchange minor
pieces. In Benoni structures, White usually tries to expand in the centre and
on the kingside. The thematic idea of putting pressure on d6 wouldn't work
well here due to the absence of the dark-squared bishop. Ideally, White would
like to expand in the centre by means of Nc4 followed by e2-e4, f2-f4 and
e4-e5. As we are going to see, however, this typical plan is not realistic
here. On the other hand, Black's main idea is to initiate a kingside expansion
with the advance ...b6-b5. Later on, he can proceed with ...c5-c4 followed by .
..Nd7-c5. Such an idea is working very well if White had already weakened the
d3-square by moving the e-pawn. Black should also put pressure on the
semi-open e-file in order to make White's central expansion difficult. In this
specific line, Black often plays ...f7-f5, anticipating the advances e2-e4 and
g2-g4. Finally, I would like to make an important clarification regarding
Black's exchange strategy. As we have already mentioned, Black tries to
exchange minor pieces in order to compensate for the lack of space. When
possible, Black should prioritize the exchange of his light-squared bishop.
This bishop is the worst piece in Benoni structures. The piece that we should
keep is the dark-squared bishop. If we exchange this bishop, besides weakening
our queenside counterplay, we will make it very easy for our opponent to
expand in the centre.} 13. Nde4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg3g4,Gg4g5] This is the most
challenging move. Besides trying the exchange Black's dark-squared bishop,
White is preparing a kingside expansion. If allowed, he will proceed with
f2-f4 followed by g3-g4-g5. Afterwards, a possible follow-up of the attack
would be the manoeuvre Rf3-h3.} ({In case of} 13. Nc4 {the simplest solution
would be} Ba6 14. Qa4 Bxc4 {Getting rid of the light-squared bishop is one of
the most important ideas for Black in Benoni structures.} 15. Qxc4 a6 $132 {
[%cal Gb6b5] Black can already start preparing ...b6-b5. At the same time,
it's very difficult for White to expand in the centre.}) 13... Be5 {Staying
true to the spirit of the Benoni, Black prefers to keep the bishop on the long
diagonal.} ({That said} 13... Be7 {is a perfectly playable alternative.}) 14.
Qd2 {The idea of this move is to take the e4-square under control.} ({In
response to the immediate} 14. f4 {Black plays} Bd4+ {Had the white queen been
on d2, White would have played e2-e3 in this position. This direction will be
examined in the theoretical lecture.}) 14... Ba6 $1 {An important multipurpose
move. Besides, pinning the e2-pawn, Black activates his light-squared bishop.
Additionally, in some positions, the bishop will be supporting the thematic
advance ...b6-b5.} 15. Rfe1 {[%cal Gf2f4] Finally, White is ready for the
advance f2-f4.} ({The direct} 15. f4 {should be answered with} Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Qe7
17. Rf3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5]} Nd7 18. g4 Rfe8 19. e3 {An important moment.
After provoking e2-e3, Black can already play} Bxc3 20. Nxc3 c4 $132 {[%cal
Gd7c5] with the thematic idea of installing a knight on d3. Black has enough
counterplay in this position.}) 15... g6 {It's important to make the g7-square
available for the bishop.} 16. f4 Bd4+ 17. e3 Bg7 {Black already enjoys a
favourable version of Benoni. The bishop pair is an important factor in the
evaluation of the position.} 18. a3 Qe7 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 19. b4 Nd7 20. g4 h6 {
I like this move. Black prevents his opponent from seizing a lot of space on
the kingside.} 21. g5 hxg5 22. Nxg5 Rfe8 23. e4 $6 {Without his dark-squared
bishop, White is not ready for this central expansion.} Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6d4]
An important move. Black is ready to force the exchange of the queens by means
of ...Qd4. The powerful bishop pair will secure a huge advantage in the
endgame.} 24. e5 {White is going for complications in order to change the
nature of the position. Tactics, however, work well for Black.} dxe5 25. d6 $2
{Decisive mistake after which Black is winning.} ({More tenacious would have
been} 25. fxe5 {Nevertheless, after} Rxe5 26. Nce4 Qd8 {White does not have
enough compensation for the pawn.}) 25... exf4 $19 26. Bxa8 Rxa8 27. Nf3 Qf5
28. Qd5 Qxd5 29. Nxd5 Bb7 30. Red1 Rd8 31. b5 Kf8 32. a4 Nf6 33. Nxf6 Bxf3 34.
Rf1 Be2 35. Rxf4 Bh6 36. Re4 Bf3 37. Ree1 Rxd6 38. Ne8 Rd8 39. Rc3 Bd2 40. Rxf3
Bxe1 0-1

