{ The following game shows how easily Black can
outplay his opponent if he manages to execute the favourable exchanges. The
first 10 moves of the game are already familiar to us} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3.
g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. d4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. Ne1
{Simplifying the position with Ne1 is a popular way to simplify the position
in QID. This approach is mostly applied by lower-rated players who are
fighting for a draw with White. In my opinion, Black's most ambitious option is
} Bxg2 11. Nxg2 c5 {This is the way to play for a win. There are three
possible pawn structures that might arise after this move: 1) Hedgehog
structure 2) dxc5 ...bxc5 structure 3) Benoni structure All three structures
lead to imbalanced positions with chances for both sides. In the game, White
decided to go for the Benoni structure after} 12. d5 exd5 13. cxd5 {In my
opinion, this version of the Benoni structure is favourable for Black in view
of the following factors: 1) Black managed to exchange 2 pairs of minor pieces,
including his typically problematic light-squared bishop 2) It seems that
Black will carry out the advance ...b6-b5 without any difficulties. In the
game, White quickly misplayed the position. 3) The poorly placed g2-knight
cannot support the central expansion} Nd7 14. e4 b5 15. Qc2 Bf6 {Obviously,
the bishop should be placed on the long diagonal.} 16. Bd2 c4 $1 {As I have
already pointed out, this advance works very well when White had already
committed to e2-e4. Black is now planning to install a knight on d3.} 17. Rad1
Ne5 18. Ne3 Re8 19. Bc3 Nd3 $17 {Black's advantage is beyond any doubt. White
decided to sacrifice an exchange but it's obvious that he does not have enough
compensation.} 20. Rxd3 cxd3 21. Qxd3 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Qc7 23. Nf5 g6 24. Nd4 Qc4
25. Qf3 b4 26. Rc1 bxc3 27. Qxc3 Qxc3 28. Rxc3 Rxe4 29. Nb5 Re1+ 30. Kg2 Rd1
31. Rc6 Rb8 32. Nc7 Rb6 33. Rc2 Kf8 34. a4 Rbb1 35. Re2 Re1 36. Rd2 a5 37. Nb5
Ke7 38. Nd4 Rbd1 39. Nc6+ Kd7 40. Rxd1 Rxd1 41. Nxa5 Rxd5 42. Nc4 Rd4 43. Nb6+
Kc6 44. a5 Kb5 45. Nd7 Kxa5 46. Kf3 Kb5 47. Ke3 Rd1 48. Nf6 h5 49. h4 Kc4 50.
Ke2 Ra1 51. Ne4 d5 52. Nd6+ Kc3 53. Nxf7 d4 54. Ne5 Ra2+ 55. Kf3 d3 0-1

