{ When Black attacks the centre with ...c7-c5, instead of allowing the
Hedgehog, White can take on c5. The structure arising after ...bxc5 is very
thematic for the Queen's Indian Defence. My experience shows that this
structure is quite decent for Black unless White has some forced way of
proving an advantage. It's interesting that old engines tended to overestimate
White's chances in such structures. The following high-profile game is quite
illustrative.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7.
Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2 Bf6 9. Ne5 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 c5 12. dxc5 ({We have
previously examined only} 12. Ng4 {leading to Hedgehog structure after} Bxd4
13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Nc6) 12... bxc5 {Statically speaking, this structure is
quite favourable for Black due to two main factors: 1) good central control 2)
possibility to put pressure on the b-file Nevertheless, one should take into
consideration the dynamic factors as well. By using his better development and
temporarily more active pieces, White tries to put pressure on Black's central
pawns. Sometimes, the d6-pawn might become vulnerable. If Black manages to
repel the immediate threats of his opponent, he will be doing fine in the long
term.} 13. Qd6 Qb6 {With this move, Black forces a transition into an endgame.}
({In the theoretical section, I will also cover} 13... Be7) 14. Rfd1 Qxd6 15.
Rxd6 Be7 16. Rd2 d6 17. Nd3 {The position is already stable and we can say
that White didn't manage to achieve anything concrete. Usually, in such
positions, the black bishop is enough to secure the protection of the d6-pawn.
At this point, Tomashevsky played a highly instructive move} a5 {Black is
gaining space on the queenside and can often fix the b2-pawn by means of ...
a5-a4. Besides that, with his last move, Black rules out any b2-b4 ideas.} 18.
e4 Nd7 $5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Gb2b3,Ga5a4] Why Tomashevsky decided to
develop the knight on this seemingly more passive square. After provoking
b2-b3 by playing ...Nb6, Black can create a queenside weakness with the help
of the advance ...a5-a4. Therefore, Vitiugov played the prophylactic} 19. a4 {
Everything, though, comes at a price. The advance a2-a4 weakens the b3-square.
Tomashevsky immediately makes use of this newly created weakness -} Rfb8 20.
Ne1 {[%cal Ge1c2,Gc2a3,Ga3b5] planning to bring the knight all the way to b5.
This operation, however, takes a lot of time. Black answered with the energetic
} Rb3 21. Nc2 Bf6 $1 {The c3-bishop is cementing the queenside. Therefore,
exchanging it makes a lot of sense.} 22. Rxd6 Bxc3 23. bxc3 Rxc3 {This move
allows White to force the transition into an equal rook endgame.} ({More
precise would have been} 23... Ne5 24. Ne3 h5 25. h4 Rxc3 $15 {In this case,
White needed to show more effort to make a draw.}) 24. Rxd7 Rxc2 25. Rb1 g6 26.
Rbb7 Rf8 27. Rb5 Rxc4 28. Rxa5 $11 Rxe4 29. Rc7 Rc4 30. Raa7 Rc2 31. Rc6 c4 32.
Rac7 Rd8 33. Rxc4 Rxc4 34. Rxc4 Rd3 35. h4 Ra3 36. Kf1 Ra2 37. Kg2 Ra3 38. Kf1
Ra2 39. Kg2 Ra3 40. Kf1 Ra2 1/2-1/2

