{This blitz game shows how dangerous dxc5 ...bxc5 structure can be with queens
on the board. In this position, instead of 14...Qb6, Oparin played} 14... a5 {
which is quite a thematic move for this pawn structure.} 15. Rfd1 ({Of course,
the c5-pawn is untouchable since after} 15. Qxc5 $4 d6 $19 {White is dropping
a piece.}) 15... Be7 16. Qd2 d6 17. Nd3 Nc6 {Black managed to stabilize his
position. It's obvious that White cannot put enough pressure on d6.} 18. e4 e5
{Preventing e4-e5 and planning to install a knight on d4 in the near future.} (
{Even more precise would have been} 18... Bf6 {It's better to put the knight
on d4 after exchanging the dark-squared bishops. White should probably play
the dynamic} 19. e5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Qd6 Qxd6 23. Rxd6 Rfb8
{Even though the draw is the most probable result, Black is the one who is
pushing for a win.}) 19. Qc2 Qb6 20. Qa4 $6 {I don't like this move. White
wants to prevent Black from expanding with ...a5-a4 but the queen goes far
away from the kingside.} Rfc8 {Probably, this cautious move is not the most
precise one.} ({Better would have been to immediately initiate kingside play
by means of} 20... f5 {[%cal Gb6b7] Black can further increase the pressure
with ...Qb7 followed by doubling the rooks on the f-file. This variation shows
the importance of Black's central control in this pawn structure.}) 21. b3 h5
22. Ne1 Nd4 $6 {It's not easy to criticize moves played in a blitz game.
Objectively speaking, however, Black shouldn't have rushed with this move.} ({
Better would have been} 22... Qb7 {[%cal Gf7f5] followed by ...f7-f5.}) 23. Qd7
$2 {This is just a waste of time. Now, Black has the possibility to regroup
his pieces in an optimal way.} ({More tenacious would have been} 23. Bxd4 cxd4
24. Nd3 Qb7 25. f3 {with inferior but probably holdable position.}) 23... Rc7
24. Qh3 g6 25. Bxd4 cxd4 26. Nd3 a4 $1 {A typical idea for this pawn structure.
In order to keep his queenside intact, White needs to allow the penetration
via the a-file.} 27. Rab1 Qb7 28. f3 axb3 29. axb3 Ra2+ 30. Kh1 Bg5 $19 {
Black's position is objectively winning. Nevertheless, in a blitz game, it's
easy to spoil any position. Eventually, this game ended in a draw.} 31. c5 Be3
32. cxd6 Rcc2 33. Ra1 Rxh2+ 34. Qxh2 Rxh2+ 35. Kxh2 Qc6 36. Nxe5 Qxd6 37. Nc4
Qb4 38. Rd3 g5 39. Kg2 g4 40. Rh1 Qb5 41. Rh4 f5 42. Rxh5 gxf3+ 43. Kh3 f2 44.
Rd1 Qxb3 45. Nxe3 Qxe3 46. Rxf5 Qe1 47. Rxd4 f1=Q+ 48. Rxf1 Qxf1+ 49. Kg4 Qe2+
50. Kf4 Qf2+ 51. Ke5 Qxg3+ 52. Kd5 Kf7 53. e5 Qf3+ 54. Kd6 Qa3+ 55. Kd5 Qb3+
56. Ke4 Qb7+ 57. Kf4 Ke7 58. Rd6 Qb4+ 59. Kf5 Qb1+ 60. Kf4 Qf1+ 61. Ke4 Qe2+
62. Kf4 Qc2 63. Rf6 Qc4+ 64. Kf5 Qd3+ 65. Kf4 Qd2+ 66. Ke4 Qe2+ 67. Kd4 Qg4+
68. Kd5 Qg2+ 69. Kd4 Qh3 70. Ke4 Qc3 71. Rd6 Qc4+ 72. Kf5 Qf1+ 73. Ke4 Qg2+ 74.
Kf4 Qf2+ 75. Ke4 Qg3 76. Rf6 Qb3 77. Rd6 Qc4+ 78. Kf5 Ke8 79. Re6+ Kf7 80. Rf6+
Ke7 81. Rd6 Qh4 82. Rf6 Qh5+ 83. Ke4 Qg4+ 84. Kd5 Qd1+ 85. Ke4 Qe2+ 86. Kd4
Qb2+ 87. Ke4 Qc3 88. Rd6 Qc4+ 89. Kf5 Qb4 90. Rf6 Qd4 91. Rd6 Qe3 92. Re6+ Kd7
93. Rd6+ Ke7 94. Re6+ Kf7 95. Rf6+ Kg7 96. Rg6+ Kh7 97. Rf6 Qd4 98. Rd6 Qe3 99.
Rf6 Qf3+ 100. Ke6 Qe4 101. Kd6 Kg7 102. Ke6 Qg4+ 103. Kd5 Qb4 104. Rd6 Qf4 105.
Rf6 Qe3 106. Kd6 Qe4 107. Ke6 Qd4 108. Rf7+ Kg6 109. Rf6+ Kg5 110. Rf5+ Kg4
111. Rf6 Qe4 112. Kd6 1/2-1/2

