{ The next
two examples taken from the correspondence practice are dedicated to Black's
setups with ...Nc6. We have already mentioned that Black often goes for ...Nc6
in order to put pressure on d4 and prepare the advance ...e6-e5. Usually, in
Queen's Indian Defence, this idea is working in combination with ...f7-f5 and .
..Bf6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4
8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. Qd3 f5 {We already know this position from the game
Fridman - Atalik. At this point, instead of 11.Qe3, White played} 11. Ne1 {
This is a typical reaction to ...f7-f5. After the exchange of the
light-squared bishops, White will try to increase the pressure on e6 by means
of e2-e4 and Nf4. Black's thematic reaction is} Bxg2 12. Nxg2 Qd7 $1 {In this
structure, it's very important to answer e2-e4 with ...fxe4 followed by ...
d6-d5. That's why Black protects the e6-pawn in advance. Additionally, with
his last move, Black prepares ...Nc6.} 13. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1d1] White does
not rush. Before going for e2-e4, he wants to mobilize his forces by means of
Bb2 followed by Rad1. Since Black has already played ...f7-f5, his best
strategy is to prepare ...e6-e5 with ...Bf6 and ...Nc6. Remember that the move
...f7-f5 almost never goes along with ...c7-c5. In such a case, when the
tension is released, Black will find himself with a shaky central pawns. He
would very much like to play the illegal ...f5-f7 move!} Bf6 14. Bb2 Nc6 15.
Rad1 Rae8 {Black has achieved his classical setup. He is getting ready for the
advance ...e6-e5. Finally, White went for} 16. e4 {Probably, the reader would
remember that Black should answer this move with} fxe4 17. Qxe4 d5 {Suddenly,
it transpires that White should take care of his d4-pawn.} 18. Qe2 dxc4 19.
Qxc4 ({After} 19. bxc4 $2 Bxd4 $19 {White does not have any compensation for
the pawn.}) 19... Na5 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the concrete solution. By gaining
an important tempo, Black is preparing the advance ...c7-c5.} ({Another decent
option would have been} 19... Qd5) 20. Qd3 c5 21. Qe4 Qb7 22. Qxb7 Nxb7 {
The position is completely equal. No surprise that the game ended in a draw.}
23. Rfe1 Kf7 24. Nf4 cxd4 25. Bxd4 e5 26. Bxe5 Bxe5 27. Rd7+ Kf6 28. Rxb7 Bxf4
29. Rxe8 Rxe8 30. gxf4 Re7 31. Rxe7 Kxe7 32. Kg2 Kd6 33. Kf3 Kc5 34. Ke4 Kb4
35. Ke5 Ka3 36. f5 a5 37. Ke6 Kxa2 1/2-1/2

