{ The next game is very similar to the previous example. The critical
position arises after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. b3 {White opts for one of the most
positional systems. His next move is going to be Bb2. Afterwards, he will
start fighting for the e4-square. Black's main continuation at this point is
10...Nd7. We are going to take a look at this move in the next game. In this
game, Black went for a different strategy -} f5 11. Bb2 Bf6 {[%cal Gd8e8,Gb7e4,
Gb8c6,Ge6e5] Besides fighting for the e4-square, Black starts gradually
preparing the advance ...e6-e5. If White does nothing special, Black is ready
to proceed with ...Qe8 followed by ...Be4, and ...Nc6. Afterwards, the advance
...e6-e5 will be on the agenda.} 12. Rad1 Qe8 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nc6 $1 {
Once again, we see that this move goes very well in combination with ...f7-f5
and ...Bf6. The advance ...e6-e5 is coming.} 15. Qf3 {White is getting ready
for the advance e2-e4. Therefore, Black immediately played} e5 $1 {Analysis
shows that this central break provides Black with enough counterplay. White
went for the most principled continuation} 16. Qxf5 ({I have also examined} 16.
Ne3 exd4 17. Nd5 Qd7 18. Nxf6+ Rxf6 19. Bxd4 Rff8 $132 {The tandem queen +
knight gives Black decent counterplay. In the future, he will be trying to
build a light square strategy.}) 16... exd4 {As a result of the exchange,
Black starts putting pressure on the e-file. White must take care of the
e2-pawn. The d4-pawn is not vulnerable at all. This pawn provides Black with a
considerable space advantage.} 17. Rfe1 Be5 18. Qe4 a5 $1 {Another important
move. The idea is to open the a-file by means of ...a5-a4.} 19. a3 d3 {Black
simplifies into an equal endgame.} 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. f4 dxe2 22. Rxe2 Nd7 23.
Qd5+ Qf7 24. Ne3 Rae8 {In this equal position, the draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

