{In this game, we will start examining White's most ambitious plan -
immediately prepare e2-e4 in order to take full control of the centre. The
first important position arises after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7
5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Nd2 {By chasing the bishop away, White prepares the
advance e2-e4. On the downside, the move 7.Nd2 spoils a bit the coordination
in White's camp. Additionally, White loses control of the important d4-square.
At this point, my suggestion would be} Bb7 ({The move} 7... Bg6 {is a
perfectly valid alternative. In my opinion, however, putting the bishop on b7
is more in the spirit of the Queen's Indian Defence.}) 8. e4 {For the time
being, White has full control of the centre. On the other hand, in order to
restore the coordination of his pieces, he needs to waste a tempo on improving
the knight. Meanwhile, Black will put the white centre under pressure. Black's
flexible pawn structure allows him to deliver various central breaks. Since
the d4-pawn is currently unprotected, Black's most logical move is} g6 {
The following next moves are obvious.} 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O d6 {
You should have a very good understanding of this structure. Depending on how
White arranges his pieces, Black would employ different strategies for
attacking the centre. Even though you should always calculate concrete
variations, I will try to provide several rules of thumb that will guide your
thinking. 1) When White plays Bg5 followed by Qd2, attacking the centre with ..
.Nc6 makes a lot of sense. The reason is that with the queen on d2, Black can
answer d4-d5 with ...Na5, threatening ...Nb3. The move ...Nc6 is often
followed by ...Na5 and ...f7-f5.2) If White plays useful waiting moves 
(instead of Bg5+Qd2) , then we should usually follow with ...Nd7 and ...e6-e5.
The King's Indian structure arising after d4-d5 is favourable for Black for
two main reasons. First of all, pair of knights has already been exchanged.
This exchange makes White's space advantage less significant. The second
reason is that White's setup with Bd2 and a2-a3 is far from ambitious. 3)
Sometimes, attacking the centre with ...c7-c5 can be an option. In this case,
however, we should usually avoid the symmetrical Benoni structure arising
after d4-d5 ...exd5 exd5. Unless Black has something very concrete, it's
difficult to create counterplay in this structure.} 12. Bg5 {This active move
is by far White's most popular choice in the position.} ({After} 12. Re1 {
I would play} Nd7 {keeping open the options of ...e6-e5 and ...c7-c5. In one
of the high-profile games, White played} 13. Bg5 {making use of the fact that
Black does not have at his disposal the setup ...Qd7 followed by ...Nc6.} ({
Of course, you should be ready for any kind of random moves such as} 13. Qc2 {
In this case, my favourite reaction is} e5 {trying to get a decent version of
King's Indian Defence.} ({As I have already pointed out, the structure arising
after} 13... c5 14. d5 exd5 ({Black should either keep the pawn on e6 or play} 
14... e5 {when the position is playable.}) 15. exd5 {does not provide Black
with sufficient counterplay. Black does not have dynamic resources to
compensate for the lack of space.}) 14. d5 ({The structure arising after} 14.
Be3 exd4 15. Nxd4 {will be dealt with in the next examples.}) 14... a5 15. b3
Nc5 {[%cal Gb7c8,Gf7f5] In my opinion, Black has nothing to worry about in
this position. He will now proceed with ...Bc8 followed by ...f7-f5. At the
same time, White's queenside play is very slow.}) 13... Bf6 {When the move ...
Qd7 is not on the table, this is the best reaction to Bg5.} 14. Bh6 ({After} 
14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qd2 e5 $11 {Black is doing fine. As we know, in all kinds of
King's Indian setups, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops works well for
Black.}) 14... Bg7 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Be3 {White finally decides to avoid the
repetition. At this point, Black played} c5 $1 {In my opinion, this is the
most precise continuation. White cannot play d4-d5 since the b2-pawn is
hanging. Therefore, White has to accept the Hedgehog structure.} 17. Qd2 cxd4
18. Bxd4 Nc5 ({In the game, Black played} 18... Ne5 {which is playable as well.
1/2-1/2 (26) Lautier,J (2596) -De Firmian,N (2610) Malmo 1999}) 19. Bc2 Bxd4
20. Nxd4 e5 {A typical way of fixing the structure in such positions. The
backward d6-pawn is compensated by the weak d4-square and Black's superior
bishop. In some cases, Black can sacrifice the d6-pawn for activity. The
following variation is quite illustrative.} 21. Nb5 Ne6 22. Red1 ({In case of} 
22. Qxd6 {Black can play for activity by means of} Qg5 {[%cal Ga8d8] followed
by ...Rad8.}) 22... Qe7 23. Nc3 Rad8 $11 {The position is equal.}) 12... Qd7
13. Qd2 Nc6 $1 {As mentioned earlier, ...Nc6 is very effective against the
combination Bg5+Qd2. White should now take care of the d4-pawn.} 14. Bc2 {
White covers both d4-pawn and b3-square but leaves c4 without protection.} ({
The most principled continuation seems to be} 14. d5 {when Black's thematic
response is} Na5 $1 {[%cal Ga5b3] The threat of ...Nb3 gives Black an
important tempo.} ({Even though} 14... Nd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 {is playable, I think
that after} 16. Rfe1 $14 {White keeps a slight edge in view of his space
advantage. Without knights on the board, Black does not have enough dynamic
resources.}) 15. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b4] It seems that White has a big advantage
since b2-b4 is already on the agenda. Black, however, can employ a very strong
thematic idea -} b5 $1 {The hyper modernist concept in its entire beauty!
Black keeps ruining White's centre. The only way for White to keep the central
structure intact is} 16. b3 {Obviously, Black shouldn't accept the exchange
sacrifice. Instead, he keeps attacking the centre by means of} exd5 17. exd5 c6
$1 {The following semi-forced sequence is quite illustrative.} 18. Bd2 Qd8 19.
Rab1 Rc8 20. Bg5 f6 21. dxc6 Bxc6 22. Be3 Bxf3 23. gxf3 f5 $132 {Even though
the position remains unclear, Black's play is easier due to White's vulnerable
king.}) ({In an internet blitz game, I faced} 14. Bh6 $2 {With limited time, I
failed to notice the elegant exchange sacrifice starting with} Nxd4 $1 ({
Instead, I opted for} 14... Bxh6 15. Qxh6 e5 16. d5 Nd8 $132 {Black will
follow with simple moves such as ...f7-f6, ...Nf7, and ...Bc8. In my opinion,
this is a decent King's Indian structure.}) 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 17. Kh1
e5 $17 {Black's advantage is out of question. White does not have open files
for his rooks. On the other hand, Black will start preparing the advance ...
f7-f5.}) 14... Na5 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] Once again, this typical move comes in
handy. This time, the idea is to prepare ...f7-f5. This advance works very
well together with ...Na5.} 15. Qe2 {Besides taking the c4-pawn under control,
White is overprotecting the knight.} ({The alternative} 15. b3 {is well met by}
f5 {[%csl Rb3]} 16. exf5 Bxf3 17. gxf3 exf5 $132 {Once again, I would take
Black in view of the better pawn structure and safer king.}) 15... f5 16. Rac1
Rae8 {[%cal Gf5e4,Gc2e4,Gd6d5,Ge8e2] By creating opposition along the e-file,
Black is preparing to ruin the centre by means of ...fxe4 followed by ...d6-d5.
} 17. Rfe1 ({Another GM game saw} 17. c5 {Black correctly reacted with} fxe4
18. Bxe4 bxc5 19. dxc5 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 d5 $15 {½-½ (27) Dreev,A (2664)
-Lorparizangeneh, S (2468) Guilan 2016. Black has an advantage in view of his
central superiority.}) 17... fxe4 18. Bxe4 d5 $1 19. Bb1 Nxc4 $6 {This move is
an inaccuracy since it allows 20.b3.} ({After the precise} 19... dxc4 20. Ne5
Qxd4 $17 {it's not easy for White to prove compensation for the missing
material.}) 20. Bd3 $2 {White makes a mistake in return.} ({The best reaction
would have been} 20. b3 Nxa3 21. Bd3 {when the a3-knight might be in trouble.
Black should go for} Rxf3 22. Qxf3 Bxd4 {and accept a very unclear position.})
20... e5 $17 {After this move, Black has a big advantage. Later on, Rapport
managed to convert it into a full point.} 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Qxc4+ Bd5 23. Qxc7
Qf5 24. Be3 Rf7 25. Qc3 Bxf3 26. gxf3 Qxf3 27. dxe5 Qg4+ 28. Kh1 Qf3+ 29. Kg1
Rxe5 30. Qd2 Qg4+ 31. Kh1 Qf3+ 32. Kg1 Qg4+ 33. Kh1 h5 34. Qd8+ Kh7 35. Qc8
Qf3+ 36. Kg1 Re4 37. Rc2 Rg4+ 38. Kf1 Qg2+ 39. Ke2 Qxh2 40. Qe6 Rf8 41. Rd1 Qg2
42. Qd7 Re4 43. Kd3 Qf3 44. Rdc1 Rd4+ 45. Qxd4 Bxd4 46. Kxd4 Rd8+ 47. Kc4 Rc8+
48. Kd3 Rd8+ 49. Kc4 Rc8+ 50. Kd3 Rxc2 51. Rxc2 g5 52. Kd2 h4 53. Rc7+ Kg6 54.
Rc8 h3 55. Bd4 Qd5 56. Kc3 h2 0-1

