{
Let's take a look at another game of Richard Rapport and try to improve his
play. The first 11 moves repeat the previous game.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4
b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Nd2 Bb7 8. e4 g6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O
11. O-O d6 12. Rb1 {As we have seen in the previous example, in many lines,
White cannot play d4-d5 because the b2-pawn is hanging. Covering b2 in advance
is the main point behind this prophylactic move.} Nd7 {This is the most
natural reaction.} ({Possible but probably not entirely sufficient is} 12...
Nc6 {In this case, White can simply protect the centre with} 13. Be3 ({Of
course, a very decent option is} 13. d5 {Since ...Na5 is impossible, Black
should go for} Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Usually, in this structure White is slightly
better due to his space advantage, In the previous example, we have seen a
similar structure with Re1 instead of Rb1. Since the move Rb1 is not very
useful in this position, Black can create counterplay by destroying White's
centre. A characteristic line would be} 15. h3 exd5 16. cxd5 c6 $1 {Without
this move, Black's position is strategically lost.} 17. dxc6 ({Starting with} 
17. Bh6 {allows} cxd5 18. Bxf8 dxe4 $44 {when Black would get decent
compensation for the exchange.}) 17... Bxc6 18. Bh6 Re8 {[%cal Gd6d5] with
sufficient counterplay. Black is ready to follow with ...d6-d5.}) 13... f5 {
The advance ...f7-f5 always comes into consideration in this pawn structure.} (
{In my opinion, White is in a decent shape to play a King's Indian structure.
For example, after} 13... e5 $6 14. d5 Ne7 15. Nd2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5] the
queenside play follows quite naturally. The next moves will be b2-b4 and c4-c5.
}) 14. exf5 exf5 15. Bc2 {Even though the position remains complicated,
White's central control gives him a slight advantage. The following line is
quite illustrative.} f4 16. Bc1 Qf6 17. Be4 g5 18. d5 Nd8 19. b4 g4 20. Bb2 Qe7
21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Nd2 $14 {with slight advantage for White. On the other hand,
everything can happen in this complicated position.}) 13. Bg5 Qc8 $6 {I find
this move a bit too passive.} ({With the knight on d7, the concept based on} 
13... f6 14. Bd2 f5 {works well for Black due to the pressure on e4.} 15. Re1
e5 {It's already not easy for White to hold the centre.} 16. Bg5 {This is the
suggestion of the computer.} ({After} 16. Ng5 {Black can go for the following
exchange sacrifice -} exd4 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 17. Ne6 Qf6 18. Nxf8 ({After} 18. Bg5
Qxe6 19. exf5 Qxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Nc5 $44 {[%cal Ga8e8] Black has more than enough
compensation for the queen. The next move is going to be ...Rae8.}) 18... Rxf8
19. exf5 Ne5 $132 {The d4-pawn, as well as the tremendous piece activity,
provide decent compensation for the exchange.}) 16... Qe8 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Nh4
$1 e4 19. Be2 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Rxf6 $132) 14. Re1 Re8 15. Qd2 c5 16. d5 exd5 17.
exd5 $14 {As we know, unless Black can do something concrete, White has a
stable advantage in this structure.} Qc7 18. Kh1 Ba6 19. b3 Nf6 20. h3 Rxe1+
21. Rxe1 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Nxe8 23. g4 Qd7 24. Kg2 Nc7 25. a4 Bc8 26. Qe3 Ne8 27.
Kf1 Bf6 28. Bf5 gxf5 29. Bxf6 fxg4 30. hxg4 Nxf6 31. Qg5+ Kf8 32. Qxf6 Qxg4 33.
Qxd6+ Kg7 34. Qe5+ f6 35. Qe7+ Kg6 36. Qe8+ Kg7 37. Qe7+ Kg6 38. Qe8+ Kg7 39.
Qe7+ 1/2-1/2

