{ The following blitz game shows a typical
tactical idea that sometimes works in this structure.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Nd2 Bb7 8. e4 g6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Nf3
O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Qc2 {Just like 12.Rb1, this is another flexible move
designed to overprotect the b2-pawn. On the downside, the d4-pawn is getting
more vulnerable now.} a5 {Black makes a useful move and at the same time keeps
the option of playing ...Nc6.} ({It goes without saying that the alternative} 
12... Nd7 {is perfectly playable.}) 13. Bg5 Qd7 14. b3 Nc6 {Black uses the
drawback of the move Qc2. White should now take care of the vulnerable d4-pawn.
} 15. Be3 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] White should already deal with the threat of ...
f5-f4.} 16. d5 {The exchange sacrifice is not entirely correct since White
does not have full compensation. As a matter of fact, White played this move
with a completely different idea in mind.} ({More to the point would have been
} 16. exf5 exf5 17. d5 {Even in this case, however, after} Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5
$15 {Black's position is preferable in view of his mobile pawn centre.}) 16...
Bxa1 17. dxc6 $4 {This is a terrible blunder.} ({Nevertheless, even after} 17.
Rxa1 Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 {it's clear that White's compensation for the exchange
is not enough.}) 17... Qxc6 18. exf5 ({When playing 16.d5, White failed to
notice that} 18. Rxa1 $2 {does not work in view of} fxe4 19. Nd4 exd3 20. Nxc6
dxc2 $19) 18... Bg7 $19 {Black is already winning.} 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 exf5
21. b5 Qd7 22. Ng5 f4 23. Bxg6 hxg6 24. Qxg6 Qf5 0-1

