{The next four games of GM Sanan Sjugirov feature a very typical and important
structure. This structure arises when Black challenges the centre with ...
e6-e5 but White keeps the tension. In such cases, Sjugirov gladly takes on d4,
getting a structure similar to the Maroczy Bind (with a pawn on c7, instead of
e7) .} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Bf4 {
This solid system is very popular at the GM level. Before putting his pawn on
e4, White wants to secure the coordination of his pieces. He is planning to
follow with e2-e3 and Bd3. Later on, he will play e3-e4 anyway.} d6 8. e3 Nd7
9. Bd3 Bb7 {Sjugirov always prefers keeping the bishops. The idea is to
achieve a complicated position with mutual chances.} ({The solid approach
based on} 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 {will be examined in the next examples.}) 10.
e4 Be7 {This move is not my theoretical suggestion. We study this game mainly
because of the pawn structure.} ({More precise is} 10... e5 {We will cover
this move in the next example.}) 11. O-O $6 {With this move, White allows
Black to get the structure he wants.} ({In my opinion, stronger would have been
} 11. Be3 {The thing is that in case of} e5 12. d5 {White's setup is good for
King's Indian type of position. That said, the position is obviously playable.}
) 11... e5 $1 {Better later than never!} 12. Be3 ({It turns out that White
cannot comfortable win a pawn. Let's take a look at some sample lines.} 12.
dxe5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 ({In case of} 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qd6 15. Nf3 O-O-O $15 {
Black's activity and bishop pair are more important than White's extra pawn.})
13... Bd6 $1 {This is the point. Black's entire concept works because of the
vulnerable f4-bishop.} 14. Qa4 {This is practically the only move.} ({After} 
14. Nxd7 Bxf4 15. Qg4 g5 {[%csl Rd7] It turns out that the knight is trapped.
White is forced to go for} 16. g3 Qxd7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. gxf4 gxf4 $17 {
[%cal Ga8g8,Gd7e6,Ge6e5] when Black has a tremendous positional advantage.
After ...Rag8, Black can even consider bringing the king to e5. It's not
difficult to see the huge difference in the activity of the bishops.}) 14...
Bxe5 15. Bxe5 O-O {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd7c5] By using the vulnerability of the white
bishops, Black is creating an interesting double threat - ...Nxe5 and ...Nc5.
White's only move is} 16. Bd4 {when after the unexpected} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Rd3,
Rd4] the bishops are still hanging. The only escape route is} 17. c5 Nc6 18.
Bb5 $1 Nxd4 19. c6 Bc8 20. Rfd1 Nf3+ 21. gxf3 Qf6 $15 {Still, Black is
slightly better in view of his superior structure and safer king.}) 12... exd4
13. Nxd4 O-O {We have finally arrived at this very important pawn structure.
Statically speaking, White has an advantage due to the space provided by the
pawns on c4 and e4. The control of the d5-square is very important in this
structure. On the other hand, Black has good squares for his minor pieces. The
knight will exert pressure from c5 while the dark-squared bishop will go to
either f6 or g5. Since pair of knights had already been exchanged, White's
space advantage is becoming less significant. Additionally, I would like to
draw your attention to important detail. As a matter of fact, the white knight
is misplaced on d4. Had the knight been on c3, the structure would have been
more favourable for White. In such a scenario, White would install a knight on
d5. When Black decides to exchange it, White will obviously take with the
c-pawn. In this case, the c7-pawn will become a perfect target. Black's main
idea in this structure is to exchange minor pieces. All endgames with only
heavy pieces on the board are favourable for Black. In such endgames, after
executing the advance ...f7-f5, Black often starts playing on the e and
f-files.} 14. f3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Gaining space and planning to fix the
queenside structure with ...a5-a4.} 15. b3 Bg5 $1 {An important move in
Black's strategy. Whenever possible, we should try to exchange minor pieces.}
16. Qd2 {Sakaev allows the exchange of the bishops.} ({In the following line,
I show what might happen if White avoids the exchange of minor pieces at any
price.} 16. Bf2 Nc5 17. Bc2 Bf6 18. Rb1 Ne6 19. Ne2 Be5 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd8g5,
Gh7h5,Gh5h4] It turns out that Black forced all white minor pieces into
passive positions. Black can already consider displaying kingside activity. A
possible idea in that direction is ...Qg5 followed by the advance of the
h-pawn.}) 16... Bxe3+ 17. Qxe3 Re8 18. Qd2 Ne5 19. Be2 Qf6 {[%cal Ge5g6,Gg6f4]
Due to the slightly weakening advance f2-f3, Black displays activity on the
dark squares by using the mighty tandem queen + knight. For instance, White
should now reckon with the idea ...Ng6-f4.} 20. Rac1 Ng6 21. g3 {Preventing ...
Nf4 but further weakening the kingside. If Black manages to deliver ...f7-f5
in the future, White's kingside will be too vulnerable.} Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e6]
True to his strategy, Sjugirov keeps trying to exchange pieces. He is now
planning ...Ne6.} 22. Qc3 Ne6 23. Nxe6 Qxe6 24. Bd3 Qh6 25. Rf2 Re5 26. Rcf1
Rae8 $15 {As a result of all the exchanges, Black managed to completely solve
his space issues. His bishop is superior to its white counterpart. Now, Black
will be trying to execute the advance ...f7-f5 under favourable circumstances.
He is already slightly better.} 27. Qd2 Qh5 28. Be2 R5e7 29. Bd3 Qc5 30. b4
axb4 31. axb4 Qd4 32. Rc1 f5 33. exf5 Re3 34. Bf1 Qe5 35. c5 Bxf3 36. cxd6 cxd6
37. Rc4 Bb7 38. Rcf4 Re1 39. f6 gxf6 40. Rxf6 Re3 41. Qxd6 Qxd6 42. Rxd6 Re1
43. Rxb6 Bd5 44. Rd6 R8e5 45. Rd7 Rb1 46. Rf4 Bc6 47. Rc7 Bb5 48. Kg2 Rb2+ 49.
Kh3 Bxf1+ 50. Rxf1 Rxb4 51. Rd1 Rh5+ 52. Kg2 Rb2+ 53. Kg1 Rb8 54. Rdd7 Rh6 55.
Kg2 Rb2+ 56. Kf3 Rf6+ 57. Kg4 1/2-1/2

