{The following fragment taken from a blitz game of Sjugirov features a typical
structural transformation. In the position on the diagram, Sjugirov played} 
14... Nc5 15. Nf5 Bg5 $1 {Once again we see this typical move. Let me remind
you that exchanging minor pieces is Black's most powerful strategy in this
structure.} 16. Rae1 ({With his last move, Black often tries to provoke} 16. f4
$6 {which is a typical mistake in this pawn structure. After} Bf6 {[%csl Re4]
the e4-pawn tends to be vulnerable. Black will increase the pressure by means
of ...Re8.}) 16... Re8 {Even though there is nothing wrong with the immediate
exchange of the bishops, Sjugirov makes a useful move with the idea to
increase the pressure on e4. At this point, White decided to opt for} 17. Bxc5
bxc5 {[%csl Rb2,Gd4][%cal Ga8b8,Ga7a5,Gc5d4] Usually, this transformation of
the pawn structure is favourable for Black. Besides increasing his central
control, Black has the possibility of playing on the semi-open b-file. It's
also important that Black obtains a bishop pair.} 18. f4 Bf6 19. Kh1 h5 {
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf6d4] Black is planning to install a bishop on d4 after ...g7-g6.}
({A bit more precise would have been to start with} 19... a5 {preventing any
b2-b4 ideas.}) 20. Ne3 Bd4 21. Nf5 Bf6 22. Ne3 Rb8 {Sjugirov is not satisfied
with the repetition and keeps playing for a win. If he managed to fix the
b2-pawn by means of ...a7-a5 he will even get an advantage. Therefore, White
played the logical} 23. b4 Bd4 24. Nf5 Qf6 25. bxc5 $6 {After this mistake,
Black has a clear advantage.} ({Better would have been} 25. b5 {with a
complicated position.}) 25... Bxc5 $15 {Black is already better in view of his
bishop pair and flexible pawn structure. Sjugirov managed to convert his
advantage.} 26. a4 g6 27. Ne3 Bc6 28. Nd5 Bxd5 29. exd5 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Rb2 31.
Qc1 Rf2 32. f5 g5 33. Qd1 g4 34. Rf1 Rb2 35. Qe1 Kg7 36. Qa5 Bb6 37. Qe1 Bd4
38. Qg3 Be5 39. Qe3 Qh4 40. f6+ Kg8 41. h3 gxh3 42. g3 Qxg3 43. Qxg3+ Bxg3 44.
Bf5 h2 45. Bh3 Kf8 46. Bd7 Be5 47. Bc6 Rd2 48. Bb5 a5 49. Bc6 Rc2 50. Bb5 Rc3
51. Bc6 Rxc4 52. Rb1 Bxf6 53. Kxh2 Be5+ 54. Kh3 Kg7 55. Rg1+ Kh6 56. Rf1 Rc3+
57. Kg2 f6 58. Bd7 h4 59. Kh1 Kg5 60. Rf5+ Kg6 61. Rf1 Bg3 62. Bf5+ Kg5 63. Bd7
Bf4 64. Rg1+ Rg3 65. Rxg3+ Bxg3 66. Kg2 Kf4 67. Be6 Ke4 68. Bg8 f5 69. Kh3 f4
70. Kg2 Ke3 71. Kf1 f3 72. Be6 Ke4 73. Kg1 Bf4 74. Kf2 Be3+ 75. Kf1 Ke5 76. Bg8
h3 0-1

