{ In the next few games, we will examine a different strategy
that Black often uses against the line with 7.Bf4. Even if you have decided to
play the system of Sjugirov, I strongly advise you to take a close look at the
following games. The pawn structure can arise via different systems in Queen's
Indian Defence.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4
7. Bf4 Be7 ({If you would like to enter Sjugirov's favourite structure, the
optimal move order would be} 7... d6 8. e3 Nd7 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. e4 e5 $1) 8. e3
d6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 {This is the solid approach to the position. I suggest that you
would use this strategy against strong opponents.} 10. Qxd3 a5 {This move is
always useful. Black not only prevents his opponent from gaining space on the
queenside but is also planning to fix the structure by means of ...a5-a4. The
position of interest arises after} 11. b3 Nd7 12. O-O O-O 13. e4 {This pawn
structure can be reached via different Queen's Indian lines. The main thing
that you should understand is that White does not have an easy way to improve
his position. Even though Black lacks space, his position is very flexible.
Therefore, White's central breaks will either backfire or provoke massive
simplifications. On the other hand, Black has many useful moves at his
disposal. In this structure, we often transfer the queen to b7 via c8. In this
way, Black not only connects the rooks but also it makes possible the advance.
..b6-b5 in some cases. Rooks are usually well placed on d8 and e8 while the
knight can be transferred to g6 via f8. It goes without saying that in any
moment, you should calculate the advances ...e6-e5, ...d6-d5, and ...c7-c5.}
Re8 14. Rfd1 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 15. e5 {White is immediately starting concrete
actions in the centre. If our pieces are not poorly coordinated, we should
never fear such attempts.} ({In case of} 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 {, Black can use
the unprotected b4-pawn and go for the concrete} e5 17. Bd2 exd4 18. Nxd4 Ne5 {
White's overextended structure provides Black with decent counterplay.}) {
Portisch decides to force the matters.} 15... dxe5 ({The waiting} 15... Qb7 {
[%cal Ga8d8,Gd7f8,Gf8g6] would have been a perfectly decent alternative.
Afterwards, Black can proceed with ...Rad8 followed by ...Nf8-g6.}) 16. Nxe5
Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Bd6 {Every exchange reduces the impact of White's space
advantage.} 18. Qg3 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Qb7 {[%cal Ga8d8] Black is ready to
challenge White's control of the d-file by means of ...Rad8.} 20. Rd4 {
Planning to double on the d-file and take the important e4-square under
control.} ({After} 20. Rd7 Rad8 21. Rad1 Rxd7 22. Rxd7 Qe4 $132 {Black has
more than enough counterplay.}) 20... Rad8 21. Rad1 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Qc6 (22... c5
23. Rd6 Qe4 $132) 23. h4 Qc5 24. Rd7 Qxa3 25. Rxc7 h6 26. Rb7 Qc1+ 27. Kh2 a4
28. bxa4 1/2-1/2

