{ The next two examples show that even if White manages
to execute both e4-e5 and d4-d5 breaks, Black has nothing to worry about. Of
course, in this case, everything depends on the coordination of Black's pieces.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Bf4 Be7 8.
e3 d6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 a5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2][%cal Ga5a4] This thematic move
can be played at any moment. Since the position is not dynamic, the exact move
order is not that important.} 11. b3 Nd7 12. e4 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. Rfd1 Qc8 {
[%cal Gc8b7]} 15. Re1 Qb7 16. Rad1 Rab8 {Black indicates that under favourable
circumstances he can consider the advance ...b6-b5.} ({In this specific
position, a decent possibility would have been} 16... d5 {You should always
consider this move when the a3-pawn is vulnerable.}) 17. d5 Bf6 18. e5 {
This advance is not dangerous for Black since he has no coordination problems.}
Nxe5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. Rxe5 exd5 22. Rxd5 Qc6 $11 {As a result
of the massive exchanges, we have reached an equal endgame with heavy pieces.
The draw was agreed in a few moves.} 23. Rd7 g6 24. h3 Re5 25. Qg3 Re1+ 26.
Rxe1 Qxd7 27. Qe5 Rd8 28. c5 1/2-1/2

