{ The
next game is a nice illustration of what might happen if White does not go for
a central break. Since we are already familiar with the first 11 moves, I will
leave them without comments.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4
6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Bf4 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 d6 11. O-O Nd7 {At this
point, instead of gaining space in the centre, White opted for} 12. Bg3 {
The idea of this waiting move is to prevent Black from playing ...e6-e5 with a
tempo.} a5 {The advance ...a7-a5 is always useful in this pawn structure. Now,
the threat is ...a5-a4.} 13. b4 {White is trying to win space on the queenside.
Nevertheless, executing the advance c4-c5 is not that easy. Usually, after
b2-b4, we would see massive simplifications on the a-file.} Qc8 $6 {Even
though the idea of transferring the queen to b7 is quite thematic for this
pawn structure, Black should have first exchanged on b4. Now, White has the
additional option of playing b4-b5.} ({More precise would have been} 13... axb4
14. axb4 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8b7] After ...Qb7, Black can start exchanging rooks on
the a-file.}) 14. Nd2 ({In my opinion, the only way to fight for an advantage
is} 14. b5) 14... Qb7 15. h3 h6 16. Rfc1 axb4 {Finally, Black is on the right
track.} 17. axb4 Ra7 {In some cases, this move allows Black to take the
control of the a-file by doubling the rooks.} ({Even simpler would have been} 
17... Rxa1 18. Rxa1 Ra8 19. Rxa8+ Qxa8 {with equality.}) 18. Ne4 Rxa1 19. Rxa1
Ra8 20. Rb1 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. c5 bxc5 23. bxc5 Qd5 $11 {The position is
completely equal. The game soon ended in a draw.} 24. Rc1 e5 ({Even better
would have been} 24... Be5) 25. cxd6 cxd6 26. Qf5 Qa5 27. dxe5 dxe5 28. Kh2 Re8
29. Rc6 Qd8 30. Ra6 Qe7 31. Qe4 g6 32. Qd5 Rd8 33. Qa5 Re8 34. Qa2 e4 35. Qa4
Be5 36. Qc4 Bxg3+ 37. fxg3 Kg7 38. Qd4+ 1/2-1/2

