{ This game is
quite similar to the previous one. In this example, however, Black even
managed to fix White's queenside with ...a5-a4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6
4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. Bf4 Be7 8. e3 a5 {I like this move order.
The idea is to provoke b2-b3 at an early stage of the game. As we have seen in
In the previous example, the advance b2-b3 makes the a3-pawn vulnerable.
Therefore, in some cases, Black has the possibility of playing ...d6-d5.} 9.
Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 a4 $1 {Unless White has something forced at his disposal,
you should always take the chance to fix the queenside.} 11. O-O d6 12. e4 Nd7
13. Rad1 {After putting his rooks on d1 and e1, White is planning to strike in
the centre.} O-O 14. Rfe1 Re8 15. e5 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6] This typical move works
perfectly well here. In many cases, Black is ready to follow with ...Ng6.} ({
Another playable option is} 15... dxe5 16. dxe5 Nc5 17. Qc2 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8a6,
Ga8d8] Black is ready follow by...Qa6 and ...Rad8. At the same time, White
does not have serious attacking chances on the kingside. For instance, the move
} 18. Ng5 {is well met by} g6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga8d8] With the dark-squared
bishops on still on the board, the advance ...g7-g6 is not risky at all.}) 16.
d5 exd5 $6 {This dubious move allows the activation of the white queen.} ({
More precise would have been} 16... dxe5 17. Nxe5 Bc5 18. Nc6 Qd7 $11 {with
complete equality.}) 17. Qxd5 dxe5 18. Qxe5 Qc8 {In return for the c7-pawn,
Black wants to obtain compensation in view of White's fixed queenside
structure.} 19. Qxc7 Ne6 20. Qxc8 Raxc8 21. Bd6 Bf6 22. Be5 {By playing this
move, White offered a draw in view of the obvious 22...Rxc4 with equality.} ({
Instead, better would have been} 22. Ne5 {For instance, after} Bxe5 23. Bxe5
Rxc4 24. Bc3 {White is better since the bishop is superior to the knight in
this position.}) 1/2-1/2

