{ Let's now
take a look at how exactly the same structure might arise from another very
popular system - 7.e3. The following high-profile game is quite illustrative.} 
1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. e3 {[%cal
Gf1d3] This seemingly modest continuation is based on a solid positional
foundation. White's next move is going to be Bd3. Only afterwards, he is going
to expand in the centre with e3-e4. Contrary to the system with 7.Bf4, in this
line, White is more flexible regarding the development of the dark-squared
bishop. Structurally speaking, however, this detail does not make too much of
a difference.} Be7 8. Bd3 Bxd3 {This is what you should play if you want to
enter our familiar pawn structure.} ({Theoretically speaking, however, even
more precise might be} 8... d5 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. Qa4+ {This position occurred
in the game Dreev,A - Sjugirov,S, 2021. At this point, Black should have played
} Nd7 $1 {when it turns out that White's attempts to utilize the pin along the
diagonal a4-e8 wouldn't provide an advantage. Let's take a look at the
following lines:} 11. Bxe4 Qxe4 12. Ne5 Qd5 {[%cal Gb6b5] Black is already
threatening ...b6-b5. Therefore, White should react quickly. The most precise
move is} 13. Qc6 ({After} 13. O-O $2 b5 14. Qa5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 $17 {
Black has a big advantage due to the healthy extra pawn.}) 13... Bf6 14. e4
Qxc6 15. Nxc6 {After the simplifications, Black has almost nothing to worry
about. The last thing that he should do is remove the c6-knight. Therefore,
the most precise continuation is} Nb8 $1 16. Nxb8 Rxb8 17. Be3 c5 18. e5 cxd4
19. Bxd4 Be7 $11 {with an equal endgame.}) 9. Qxd3 d6 10. e4 Nd7 11. O-O a5 12.
Bf4 {Finally, we have reached a typical position for the line with 7.Bf4.} ({
Let's take a look at the alternative way of developing the bishop -} 12. b3 O-O
13. Bb2 {In this case, I think that we can opt for another familiar structure
by playing} e5 {Of course, we play this move only after calculating that
taking on e5 is not dangerous for us. The most sensible move seems to be} 14.
Rad1 ({After} 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. Bxe5 {Black's
activity and control of the d-file provides more than enough compensation. The
most precise move seems to be} a4 ({Of course,} 17... Rd3 $5 $132 {is
perfectly playable as well.}) 18. Bxc7 Rdc8 19. Bxb6 axb3 $11) 14... exd4 15.
Nxd4 Bf6 {[%cal Gd7c5] We have already dealt with this structure when
analyzing the games of Sanan Sjugirov. Besides putting pressure on the centre,
Black's main strategy is to exchange minor pieces.}) 12... O-O ({Obviously,
Black could have considered} 12... a4) 13. Rad1 Qc8 14. e5 dxe5 {By now, our
reader should understand that taking quickly on e5 is not forced. Before going
for this capture, you need to evaluate whether the move dxe5 gives White
sufficient attacking chances. In this case, White does not have serious
attacking potential since 2 pairs of minor pieces have already been exchanged.
Also, it's clear that more exchanges will occur on the open d-file.} ({A
pretty decent alternative would have been} 14... Re8 {In my opinion, the
following sequence makes a lot of sense.} 15. Rfe1 Qb7 16. h4 Rad8 17. h5 h6
18. Qe2 dxe5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Bd6 $11 {After the exchange of the bishops,
Black has nothing to worry about.}) 15. dxe5 Nc5 16. Qc2 h6 {[%cal Gf8d8] In
this structure, it's important to take the control of the g5-square. Otherwise,
we should always reckon with moves like Bg5 and Ng5. Gulko is now ready to
follow with ...Rd8.} 17. Be3 Rd8 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Nd4 Qe8 20. b4 axb4 21.
axb4 Na6 22. b5 Nb4 23. Qe4 Ra4 {[%cal Ge8a8] In this equal position, the draw
was agreed. Black is ready to invite more exchanges by playing ...Qa8.} 1/2-1/2

