{ In this game, we shall take a brief look
at 6.Qc2. As we will see in a while, this move is not very challenging for
Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Qc2 {White
immediately puts pressure on the e4-knight but wastes valuable time on playing
with the queen. Black's most natural reaction is} Nxc3 7. Qxc3 Be7 {[%cal
Ge8g8,Gc7c5] Black's plan is simple. After castling, he will strike in the
centre with ...c7-c5.} 8. e3 ({In case of} 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 d6 {we get a type
of position that is typical for the system with 4.g3. We have already dealt
with this structure.}) 8... O-O 9. Bd3 c5 {The most principled choice.} 10. d5
({Clearly worse is} 10. O-O $6 Bxf3 11. gxf3 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc6 $17 {[%cal
Gf7f5] Black is clearly better in view of his better structure and safer king.
His next move will be ...f7-f5.}) {In my opinion, this is not the most precise
move.} 10... d6 ({Black should have opted for the following sequence -} 10...
exd5 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qd3+ Kg8 14. Qxd5 Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7,Gd7d5]
Obviously, Black is planning to proceed with ...Nc7 followed by ...d7-d5.
White can try to generate kingside activity with} 15. h4 {Nevertheless, after}
Nc7 16. Qf5 d5 {[%cal Gd8c8]} 17. h5 Qc8 $11 {Black manages to neutralize the
pressure.}) 11. e4 Nd7 12. h4 Bf6 13. Qc2 Ne5 14. Ng5 h6 15. f4 Nxd3+ 16. Qxd3
e5 17. f5 b5 18. Nf3 bxc4 19. Qc2 Qb6 20. g4 Qb3 21. Qxb3 cxb3 22. g5 Bd8 23.
gxh6 g6 24. Rg1 Kh8 25. Bg5 gxf5 26. Bxd8 Raxd8 27. Rg7 fxe4 28. Ng5 Bxd5 29.
O-O-O f6 30. Nh7 Rf7 31. Rdg1 f5 32. Ng5 Rfd7 33. Rg6 e3 34. Rf6 f4 35. h7 c4
36. Rd1 Kg7 1/2-1/2

