{ The system with 6.Qc2 allows Black to create imbalances right from
the opening. The following encounter is a typical example.} 1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 b6
3. c4 Bb7 4. a3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Ne4 6. Qc2 Nxc3 7. Qxc3 Qf6 $5 {A very interesting
way of preventing the advance e2-e3. If you want to play this system, you
should be psychologically ready to exchange your light-squared bishop for the
f3-knight.} 8. g3 {This move leads to the type of play Kovaleko was looking
for.} ({According to the engine, more precise is} 8. Bg5 $1 {In this case, a
possible follow-up would be} Qf5 9. g3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxf3 11. exf3 Nc6 $132 {
Black's better pawn structure provides good compensation for White's bishop
pair. Even though White might be objectively slightly better, all the
imbalances allow Black to play for a win.}) 8... Bxf3 {Kovalenko immediately
seizes the opportunity to create imbalance.} ({The computer, however, affirms
that even more precise is} 8... c5 $1 {when White does not have a reliable way
to cover the d4-pawn. A possible follow-up would be} 9. Bg5 cxd4 10. Bxf6 dxc3
11. Bxc3 Na6 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga6c5,Gc5a4] Black is slightly better since
after Bg2 the c4-pawn will be vulnerable. Black can follow with simple moves
like ...Rc8 and ...Nc5.}) 9. Qxf3 Qxf3 10. exf3 Nc6 $132 {Black obtained the
type of position he wanted. Later on, Kovalenko managed to outplay his
opponent.} 11. Be3 a5 12. Rc1 Be7 13. d5 Nd8 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Bd3 Bc5 16. Be4
Rb8 17. Rd1 Nf7 18. Bf4 Bd6 19. Be3 Ke7 20. Ke2 h6 21. h4 Bc5 22. Bf4 Rhc8 23.
h5 b5 24. cxb5 Rxb5 25. Rd2 Bd6 26. Be3 Be5 27. Rb1 Bf6 28. f4 Rxh5 29. Bg6 Rd5
30. Rxd5 exd5 31. Bd2 Ra8 32. b3 Nd6 33. Kd3 c5 34. Be3 Rc8 35. Rd1 Nb5 36. Rc1
Kd6 37. a4 Nd4 38. Bxd4 Bxd4 39. f3 Rb8 40. Rb1 Bf2 41. g4 Rb4 42. f5 Bh4 43.
Kc2 Bf6 44. Bf7 Bg5 45. Rd1 d4 46. Re1 Be3 47. Kd3 Ke5 48. Re2 d5 49. f4+ Kd6
50. Rc2 Rxb3+ 0-1

