{With this game, we start dealing with a very important structure that often
arises in the line with 4.e3. At the same time, the same structure can be
reached in different systems as well.} 1. Nf3 ({Our usual move order will be} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nc3 Bd6 8. O-O
O-O 9. b3 a6 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Rc1 Qe7 {when we reach the position from the
game.}) 1... d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 b6 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. d4 Bd6 8.
Bd3 O-O 9. O-O a6 10. Rc1 Qe7 11. cxd5 exd5 {Finally, we got to the important
pawn structure. White's play is based on two key ideas: 1) pressure on the
c-file 2) fight for the important e5-square Very often White executes the
manoeuvre Ne2-g3. Besides protecting the king, this manoeuvre is designed to
provoke the advance ...g7-g6. After ...g7-g6, White often tries to open the
big diagonal for his bishop, even at the price of some sacrifices. On the
other hand, Black has control of the e-file and the e4-square. His first
priority is to install a strong knight on e4. Afterwards, his main plan is
based on a kingside attack. In the following model games, we are going to
examine different attacking ideas for Black.} 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3e5]
Always pay attention to his move. By increasing the pressure on the c-file,
White creates the threat of Ne5. After multiple exchanges on e5, White will
finally collect the c7-pawn. Therefore, Navara protects this important pawn in
advance with} Rac8 14. Ng3 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc2e2,Gg3f5] White goes for the
familiar typical idea. He is now threatening Nf5. Black's classical antidote is
} ({In case of} 14. Nf4 {Black can even opt for the aggressive} g5 15. Ne2 ({
After} 15. Nh5 f5 {[%cal Gc8e8,Gf5f4] we shouldn't underestimate the potential
of Black's attack. He is already planning to follow with ...Rce8 and ...f5-f4.
A possible follow-up would be} 16. Qe2 Rce8 $1 {The attack is more important
than the defence of the a6-pawn.} 17. Bxa6 Bxa6 18. Qxa6 f4 $17 {[%cal Ge7f7]
Black had a huge advantage in the game 1-0 (43) Spoelman,W (2573) -Keymer,V 
(2502) Germany 2018. The next move is going to be ...Qf7}) 15... f5 16. Ng3 {
This position was reached in the game Peptan, C - Javakhishvili, L, 2021. At
this point, Black should have played} Rf7 $1 {[%cal Gc8e8,Gf5f4] planning to
follow with ...Rce8 and ...f5-f4.} 17. Qe2 a5 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 18. Rc2 f4 $40 {
with an attack.}) 14... g6 ({A bit later, we will deal with the concept based
on} 14... Nxg3) 15. Qe2 {This move is the reason why White provoked ...Rac8 by
playing 13.Qc2. Now, the a6-pawn is under attack. Nevertheless, White is not
threatening to win a pawn since in the end of the line, Black will play ...Ra8
followed by ...Rxa2. Hence, Navara played} h5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3] A thematic
idea in this pawn structure. Black wants to provoke kingside weaknesses by
pushing the pawn all the way to h3. Once White commits himself to g2-g3, Black
can consider opening the centre with ...c7-c5.} 16. Ne5 {Feeling the danger,
Harikrishna correctly decides to simplify into an equal endgame.} ({We can see
a very good illustration of Black's ideas in the following variation:} 16. Rfd1
h4 17. Nf1 h3 18. g3 c5 $5 {In my opinion, this is the most precise move.} 19.
dxc5 Ndxc5 {Once we have managed to provoke g2-g3, this version of IQP is
favourable for us. If White blocks the pawn with Nd4, he reduces the number of
kingside defenders. Additionally, Black can always exchange the knight by
means of ...Ne6. Another problem for White is that Black is planning to follow
with ...Nxd3 and ...Ba3. After the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, Black
can make use of the vulnerable c3-square.} 20. Nd4 {This seems to be the most
natural move.} ({In case of} 20. Bb1 {Black can immediately play} Ne6 {White
should already reckon with the advance ...d5-d4. Meanwhile, Black can always
use the g5-square for one of his knights. In such positions, the h3-pawn gives
a lot of dynamic potential. The following non-forced sequence is a good
illustration of what might happen.} 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Bc5 {By exchanging
the dark-squared bishops, Black wants to weaken the c3-square. If White
decides to cover the c3-square by means of} 23. Qb2 {Black strikes on the
other wing -} Ng5 $19 {[%cal Gg5f3,Gc5a3] with a winning position in view of
the double threat - ...Nf3+ and ...Ba3.}) 20... Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Ba3 22. Bxa3 Qxa3
$17 {For White is not easy to keep the c3-square under control, protect the
a2-pawn, and fight for the c-file. Black already has a big advantage.}) 16...
Nxe5 {This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence leading to an equal
endgame.} 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 Qxe5 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bxa6 Bxa6 21. Qxa6 Ra8
22. Qe2 Rfd8 $11 {The position is completely equal. It's not a surprise that
the game finally ended in a draw.} 23. Rfd1 Rd3 24. Rxd3 exd3 25. Qxd3 Rxa2 26.
Qd4 Qxd4 27. exd4 Rd2 28. h3 Rxd4 29. Rxc7 Rd3 30. Rb7 Rxb3 31. g4 hxg4 32.
hxg4 g5 33. Kf1 Kg7 34. Rd7 Rb4 35. Rd6 b5 36. Rb6 f6 37. Rb7+ Kf8 38. Ke2 Re4+
39. Kd3 Rb4 40. Ke3 Ke8 41. f3 Kf8 42. Ke2 Rb3 43. Kf2 Ke8 44. Ke2 b4 45. Kf2
Kd8 46. Ke2 Rb1 47. Kd3 b3 48. Ke4 Kc8 49. Rb4 b2 50. Kf5 Rf1 51. Rxb2 Rxf3+
52. Ke6 Kc7 53. Rb5 Rf4 54. Rf5 Rxg4 55. Kxf6 Kd6 56. Rxg5 Rxg5 57. Kxg5 Ke5
1/2-1/2

