{ In this example, GM
Kryvoruchko demonstrated a powerful concept against the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-g3.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. O-O Bd6 8. b3
Qe7 {This is the correct move order.} ({The careless} 8... O-O $6 {would allow
the move} 9. Ba3 {In this structure, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops
is obviously favourable for White.}) 9. Bb2 {[%cal Gf3e5] Now, White is
planning to establish a knight on e5. Therefore, Black should start with} Nbd7
10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] With every move, White wants something. Now, the threat
is Nb5. That's why Black plays} a6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Ng3 {In the
previous example, White started with 13.Qc2. In this concrete case, the move
order is not that important. Now, instead of thematic ...g7-g6, Black played}
Nxg3 $5 {The idea is that after} 14. hxg3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] the other knight
will occupy the e4-square. In view of the doubled pawns on g2 and g3, White
cannot easily chase the black knight away by playing f2-f3. Meanwhile, after
establishing a knight on e4, Black can consider the advance ...h7-h5-h4. In my
opinion, this is the best concept when we are playing for a win.} 15. Ne5 Ne4 {
[%cal Gf7f6] It turns out that the e5-knight is not threatening at all. Black
is ready to follow with ...f7-f6.} 16. Bxe4 {Sooner or later White opts for
this move since it's impossible to live with the e4-knight for too long. With
his last move, White also frees the c4-square for the knight.} ({Nothing
changes after} 16. Qh5 f6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nc4 a5 {when it's very likely that
we will get the same type of opposite-coloured bishops middlegame, as in the
game. In this concrete case, Black has the additional possibility of ...a5-a4.}
) 16... dxe4 17. Nc4 Bd5 $1 {This is a key move in Black's concept. Black
already anticipates the middlegame with opposite coloured bishops. By blocking
the d4-pawn, Kryvoruchko prevents his opponent from activating the bishop by
means of d4-d5. Additionally, with a bishop on d5, Black can already play ...
c7-c6, eliminating White's pressure on the c-file.} 18. Nxd6 $6 {This move
makes Black's advantage even bigger. On the other hand, suggesting a
constructive idea for White is far from easy.} Qxd6 $17 {The arising
middlegame with opposite-coloured bishops is clearly better for Black. In such
middlegames, the possibility to organize a kingside attack is what matters.
The e4-pawn provides a lot of space on the kingside. Therefore, Black will
easily create kingside activity. Later on, even with some inaccuracies,
Kryvoruchko managed to convert his advantage.} 19. Qg4 c6 20. Qf4 Qd7 21. g4
Rfe8 22. Qf5 Qd6 23. Qf4 Qd8 24. Rc2 Re6 25. f3 Qh4 ({Even simpler would have
been} 25... h6 $19 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8e8,Ge6g6]}) 26. g5 Qxf4 27. exf4 exf3 28.
gxf3 Rae8 29. Bc1 f6 30. Kf2 f5 31. Rh1 a5 32. Rd1 Kf7 33. Rh1 Kg6 34. Rb2 h5
35. gxh6 gxh6 36. Rc2 b5 37. Rb2 Kh7 38. Rg1 Ra8 39. Re2 Rxe2+ 40. Kxe2 a4 41.
bxa4 bxa4 42. a3 Rb8 43. Rg3 Rb3 44. Rh3 Kg6 45. Rg3+ Kf7 46. Rh3 h5 47. Be3
Kg6 48. Rg3+ Kh6 49. Bc1 h4 50. Rh3 Kh5 51. Bd2 Bc4+ 52. Kf2 Rxa3 53. Bb4 Ra2+
54. Kg1 Ra1+ 55. Kf2 a3 0-1

