{The following fragment taken from the game Gelashvili, T - Adams, M shows
that Black can apply the concept of Kryvoruchko even when White had played Qc2
beforehand.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. O-O Bd6 7. Nc3
O-O 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2 a6 {[%cal Gd8e7] Sooner or later, we need to play this
move. Now, the idea is to prepare ...Qe7.} ({The immediate} 9... Qe7 {is well
met by} 10. Nb5) 10. Rc1 Qe7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3e5]}
Rac8 14. Ng3 Nxg3 {I think that this is once again the best move. Taking on h7
with a check is not dangerous.} ({In the game, Adams played} 14... g6 15. Qe2
Rfe8 16. Rc2 h5 {which is the plan that we have seen in the game Harikrishna -
Navara.} 17. Rfc1 ({Just like in the abovementioned game, White could have
bailed out with} 17. Ne5 {As we know, the sequence} Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bxe5 19. Bxe5
Qxe5 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxa6 Bxa6 22. Qxa6 Rcd8 $11 {results in an equal
endgame.}) 17... h4 18. Nf1 h3 19. g3 b5 $1 {We can often see the advance ...
b6-b5 in this pawn structure. Besides protecting the a6-pawn, Black gains
space on the queenside and takes the control of the c4-square. The next move
is going to be ...c7-c5 with the threat of ...c5-c4.} 20. a4 $6 {This move
only creates additional queenside targets for Black.} ({The computer suggests} 
20. Ne1 c5 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Qg4 {Even in this case, however, after} Qe6 23.
Qh4 Bd5 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 24. dxc5 Be5 $15 {Black has tremendous compensation for
the pawn due to his space advantage and piece activity.}) 20... bxa4 21. bxa4
c5 22. dxc5 Ndxc5 $17 {We have already discussed this structure. In this
concrete position, the vulnerable a4-pawn creates additional problems for
White. Black has a big advantage.}) 15. hxg3 ({After} 15. Bxh7+ $2 Kh8 16. hxg3
g6 17. Bxg6 fxg6 18. Nh4 Qe6 $17 {White does not have compensation for the
sacrificed material.}) 15... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 16. Ne5 Ne4 {It turns out that
even with a queen on c2, this setup works quite well for Black.} 17. Bxe4 ({
Of course, I have checked} 17. f3 $2 {which is the most logical way to justify
the setup with Qc2. It turns out, however, that White's idea does not work
tactically.} Nxg3 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. f4 {[%cal Gf1f3]} Bxe5 20. dxe5 ({Nothing
changes} 20. fxe5 Nxf1 21. Rxf1 g6 22. Bxg6 fxg6 $19 {with a winning position
for Black.}) 20... d4 $19 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ge7h4,Gb7g2] Black is already
winning.}) 17... dxe4 18. Nc4 f6 $15 {[%cal Gb7d5] Black's next move is going
to be ...Bd5. If White takes on d6, we get the same type of middlegame as in
the game Kosic, D - Kryvoruchko, Y.} ({The immediate} 18... Bd5 $2 {loses to}
19. Nxb6 cxb6 20. Qxc8 $18) *

