{ Sometimes, White refrains from the
move Ne2-g3. In this case, the advance of the h-pawn makes less sense. In such
cases, Black can seriously consider gaining more space with ...f7-f5. The
following game is quite illustrative. I leave the first 12 moves without
comments since they are already familiar to us.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
4. e3 b6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3]} Qe7 9. Bb2 Bb7
10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5]} a6 11. Rc1 Nbd7 12. Ne2 Ne4 {At this point, instead of
the usual move 13.Qc2 and 13.Ng3, White played} 13. Rc2 {[%cal Gd1a1,Gf3e5,
Gf1c1] The idea is to prepare Qa1 followed by Ne5. Of course, White can
consider doubling the rooks on the c-file. The drawback of this concept is
that the white queen will be isolated from the battle. Leko reacted in a very
convincing way -} f5 14. Qa1 Rae8 {Black has already mobilized his forces and
can plan his kingside activity. Therefore, White should play energetically.
The Polish grandmaster opted for the immediate} 15. Ne5 {The point of White's
concept. It turns out, however, that Leko was quite well prepared for this
idea.} Bxe5 $1 {[%csl Rd3] The most precise continuation. Black makes use of
the restricted d3-bishop.} ({Obviously, after} 15... Nxe5 $2 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17.
Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Qxe5 Rxe5 19. Rxc7 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) 16. dxe5
Nec5 {[%csl Rd3] This is the point.} 17. Nd4 {Dziuba goes for a creative
approach. Objectively speaking, however, White's compensation is not enough.} (
{The computer suggests} 17. e6 Nxe6 18. Nd4 {White is planning to answe 18...
Nxd4 with the intermediate 19.Rxc7. Black, however, can play} Ndc5 {when the
following sequence seems to be more or less forced -} 19. Ba3 Qh4 20. Nxe6 Rxe6
21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. Rxc5 Rg6 $132 {Black's kingside activity provides enough
compensation for the spoiled structure. White should reckon with the advance ..
.d5-d4. It's important to point out that the tempting} 23. Qd4 $4 {loses to}
Qh3 24. g3 f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] with the threat of ...f4-f3. After} 25. exf4 Rh6
26. Re1 Qxh2+ 27. Kf1 Qh1+ 28. Ke2 Re6+ $19 {Black is winning.}) ({In case of} 
17. Rd1 {Black solves his problems by means of} Nxd3 18. Rxd3 c5 $11 {Even
though the position seems dynamically balanced, I decided to examine it a bit
further. The following sequence is forced -} 19. Nf4 Nxe5 20. Nxd5 Qd6 21. Bxe5
Qxe5 22. Qxe5 Rxe5 23. Rcd2 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 Bxd5 25. Rxd5 Rc8 26. Rxf5 c4 27.
bxc4 Rxc4 28. h4 Ra4 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) 17... Nxd3 18. Rxc7 {This is
White's idea. The next moves are quite forced.} N3c5 19. e6 Qd6 20. exd7 Rd8
21. b4 Qxc7 22. bxc5 Qxd7 23. cxb6 Rf6 $17 {Finally, the dust has settled.
It's already clear that White's compensation for the exchange is not enough.
Peter Leko managed to convert his advantage.} 24. Bc3 Rc8 25. Qb2 Rg6 26. g3
Rc4 27. Rb1 Qc8 28. Ba5 h6 29. Qd2 Rf6 30. h4 Qe8 31. Bc3 Qg6 32. Qd3 f4 33.
Qxg6 Rxg6 34. Be1 fxe3 35. fxe3 Rf6 36. Kg2 h5 37. Rb2 Kf7 38. Bd2 Ke8 39. g4
hxg4 40. Kg3 Kd7 41. Kxg4 Rg6+ 42. Kf3 Rc8 43. Rb1 a5 44. Bxa5 Rf8+ 45. Ke2
Rg2+ 46. Kd1 Rf1+ 47. Be1 Rxe1+ 0-1

