{
Sometimes, after the moves} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. e3 d5 6.
cxd5 exd5 {Instead of playing the immediate 7.Bd3, White starts with} 7. Bb5+ {
and only after} c6 {he goes back to d3 -} 8. Bd3 {By provoking the advance ...
c7-c6, White reduces Black's control of the e4-square. Now, he has two plans
at his disposal: 1) Go for the usual setup based on b2-b3 followed by Bb2 2)
Apply the Pilsbury plan by means of Ne5 followed by f2-f4 In this game, my
opponent went for the first approach. With the move ...c7-c6 included, it's
very important to start with} Be7 $1 {The idea is that Black wants to answer
Ne5 with ...c7-c5 followed by ...Nc6, putting pressure on d4. Being on e7 
(instead of d6) , the bishop does not close the way of the queen. Therefore,
the d5-pawn is safely protected. Additionally, if we combine the moves ...Bd6
and ...c6-c5, we must reckon with Nb5-based ideas. What is even more important
is to keep the b8-knight flexible. If White goes for b2-b3 followed by Bb2, we
will develop the knight to d7. The knight goes to c6, only if White applies
the Pilsbury approach based on Ne5.} ({If we start with} 8... Nbd7 {White can
play} 9. Ne5 {White's idea becomes clear after} Bd6 $6 ({Obviously, Black
should play} 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 $13 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd1c2,Ge1c1] with
a very unclear position.}) 10. f4 {This version of the Stonewall structure 
(with colours reversed) is favourable for White. It's not easy for Black to
deal with the e5-knight. Since we have already committed to ...c7-c6, the move
... Ne4 is impossible. On the other hand, the advance ...c6-c5 does not work
well in combination with ...Nbd7. The d7-knight is heavily restricted by the
d4-pawn.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 Re8 11. Bb2 Bd6 {Once White's plan became clear,
we can opt for our usual setup. One might argue that the Black bishop wasted
two tempis to reach the d6-square. At the same time, however, White also
wasted a tempo by giving a check on b5. Additionally, having played ...c7-c6,
Black does not need the move ...a7-a6.} 12. Qc2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf6e4] Black
is ready to occupy the e4-square by means of ...Qe7 followed by ...Ne4. In the
game, Georgiev played the classical} 13. Ne2 ({It's very important to consider
} 13. e4 $6 {This is the only way to take advantage of the move ...c7-c6.
Fortunately, after} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bd3 c5 $15 {Black is
even overtaking the initiative in view of the threat of ...Bxf3.}) 13... Qe7
14. Ng3 g6 15. Rfe1 Ne4 {It's clear that Black solved all his problems. White
does not have any constructive ideas. Now, Black should decide how to organize
his kingside attack.} 16. Nd2 f5 17. Ngf1 Ndf6 18. Nf3 {White's idea is simple.
Whenever the black knight leaves the d7-square, White is threatening to
install a knight on d7. Since this was a team competition, and the draw was
good for my team, I accepted the repetition.} Nd7 19. N3d2 Ndf6 ({If Black
wants to continue the game, he should play something like} 19... Rac8 20. Rac1
c5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 $36 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge7h4] Black has the initiative. The piece
activity provides more than enough compensation for the isolated pawn.}) 20.
Nf3 Nd7 21. N3d2 Ndf6 1/2-1/2

