{ The next two model games provide a very good
illustration of how to fight against the plan based on Ne5. In the first
example, the legendary Artur Jussupow is completely outplayed. Even though
this is just a blitz game, the play of GM Fedorchuk is quite instructive.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 {This time, we will get out position via the
Zukertort move order.} Bb7 5. O-O Be7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
c5 {Exactly the same position could arise via the Queen's Indian move order.
Black is now planning to put pressure on White's centre by means of ...Nc6.}
10. f4 Nc6 $1 {This is the key move. It turns out that White cannot
simultaneously take care of the d4-pawn and cover the e4-square. The main
drawback is the vulnerable d4-pawn.} 11. Qf3 {This thematic move is designed
to take the e4-square under control. Additionally, in some cases, the queen
can be transferred to g3 or h3.} ({The attempt to protect the d4-pawn by means
of} 11. Ne2 {is well met by} Ne4 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] when White does not have
any attacking chances. Black can chase the e5-knight away whenever he wants.
Meanwhile, Black is ready to expand on the queenside by means of ...a7-a5-a4.
In this case, the idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops via a6 is
always on the agenda.}) 11... cxd4 {Black immediately uses the drawback of
White's last move. In order not to lose a pawn, White is forced to part with
the pride of his position - the e5-knight. Jussupow played} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13.
exd4 Re8 {The position has stabilized and we can already draw some concrete
conclusions. Had White the possibility to make an illegal move, his choice
would have been f4-f2! Fighting for the e4-square is Black's main positional
idea. It goes without saying that after exchanging the light-squared bishops,
he wants to install a knight on e4. A possible idea is ...Qd7 followed by ...
b6-b5-b4. After kicking the knight back, Black can exchange the light-squared
bishops via b5.} 14. f5 Ne4 {[%cal Ge7f6] This move marks the beginning of a
well-calculated operation. Black is planning to increase the pressure on d4 by
means of ...Bf6.} ({Another very interesting possibility would have been} 14...
b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd8d7,Gd8b6,Gc6b5] Accepting the pawn sacrifice is risky.
For instance, after} 15. Bxb5 Bxb5 16. Nxb5 Qb6 $17 {Black will regain the
pawn under favourable circumstances. Besides his poor development, White has a
vulnerable king.}) 15. Bf4 ({The tactical point behind Black's last move is
that} 15. Nxe4 $2 {will be answered with} dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxd4+ $19 {when Black
is winning a piece.}) 15... Bf6 16. Ne2 Qd7 17. g4 h6 {Preventing any
counterplay. Black can already exchange the light-squared bishops via b5.} 18.
Rad1 Bb5 19. Be5 {A mistake in a strategically lost position. After} Bxd3 20.
Qxd3 Bxe5 21. dxe5 Rxe5 $19 {Black got a decisive advantage.} 22. Nf4 Nf6 23.
h3 Rae8 24. b3 Qd6 25. Kg2 Re3 26. Qb5 R8e4 27. Rxd5 Nxd5 28. Qxd5 Re2+ 29. Kg1
Qxd5 30. Nxd5 Rd4 31. Nc3 Re3 32. Rc1 Rd2 33. a4 Rg3+ 34. Kf1 Rxh3 35. Ne2 Rh1+
36. Ng1 Rd4 37. Kg2 Rh4 38. Rc8+ Kh7 39. Nf3 Rhxg4+ 40. Kh3 Rdf4 41. Ne5 Rg5
42. Nxf7 Rgxf5 43. Rh8+ Kg6 44. Nd6 Rf6 45. Rd8 Rd4 0-1

