{Sometimes, in the system with 4.e3, Black can go for a position with hanging
pawns. Nevertheless, we will apply this strategy only when we can get 100
percent favourable version of the hanging pawns. Let's take a look at two
instructive examples. Since we are familiar with the first 10 moves, I will
leave them without comment.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5
6. b3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Nc3 a6 10. Rc1 Qe7 {Black has already
arranged his pieces in an optimal way. If White takes on d5, we will reach our
familiar structure. On the other hand, if White keeps delaying cxd5, Black can
often consider ...dxc4 followed by ...c7-c5. Of course, Black can always play
the standard ...Ne4. In the game, White played} 11. Na4 {After this move,
Black should already reckon with moves like c4-c5 and b3-b4. The drawback of
this approach is that the white knight goes far away from the centre.
Therefore, Black's most logical reaction seems to be} ({In case of} 11. Qc2 {
taking the e4-square under control, my suggestion would be} dxc4 12. bxc4 Bxf3
13. gxf3 c5 $132 {when Black has decent counterplay due to his favourable
structure and White's vulnerable king.}) 11... dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 {In positions
with hanging pawns, the white knight definitely does not belong to a4. The
hanging pawns arose after} 13. Ne5 Rad8 14. f4 cxd4 15. exd4 {Let's briefly
discuss this fundamental pawn structure. Since the hanging pawns provide a lot
of space, the side playing with them often manoeuvres his pieces towards the
opponent king. At the same time, the hanging pawns create a lot of dynamic
potential. For example, the side playing against such pawns should always
watch for the advance of one of the pawns. On the downside, in the long run,
hanging pawns are vulnerable. When you play against hanging pawns, always try
to exchange pieces and achieve an endgame. At the same time, the hanging pawns
can be attacked two thematic pawn breaks - ...e6-e5 and ...b6-b5. In this
concrete position, the inclusion of the moves ...a7-a6 and Na4 makes the break
...b6-b5 quite realistic. This is what Black is playing for. He started with}
Ba3 {Black immediately starts exchanging pieces.} 16. Qb3 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Rb8 $6
{[%cal Gb6b5] Black is already preparing the thematic ...b6-b5. In fact, this
move is not the optimal solution. Nevertheless, this move makes the game
instructive.} ({Black could have used White's vulnerable centre by means of} 
17... Nxe5 18. fxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5] White is under huge pressure since Black
has multiple threats. Besides the standard ...Ne5, White should watch for
active moves such as ...Qh4, ...Qg5, and even ...Nxh2. Black is already better.
}) 18. Rce1 $6 {White is returning the favour.} ({Better would have been} 18.
Nc3 {when White restores his coordination and prevents the advance ...b6-b5.})
18... b5 $1 {This thematic break already works quite well.} 19. cxb5 axb5 20.
Bxb5 Qd6 $44 {Black has full compensation for the pawn in view of his better
coordination, superior pawn structure and safer king. Later on, he even
managed to win.} 21. Nc4 Qc7 22. Rc1 Ba6 23. Nc3 Qa7 24. Rfd1 Bxb5 25. Nxb5 Qa4
26. Ncd6 Nd5 27. Qa3 Qxa3 28. Nxa3 Ra8 29. Nac4 Nxf4 30. Rd2 Nd5 31. Rb2 Ra6
32. Rb7 N7f6 33. a3 Ng4 34. Rf1 Nge3 35. Nxe3 Rxd6 36. Nxd5 Rxd5 37. a4 Rxd4
38. Ra1 Rd6 39. a5 Ra6 40. Kf2 Rfa8 41. Ke3 Kf8 42. Rb5 Ke7 43. Kd4 R8a7 44.
Kc5 e5 45. Kb4 f6 46. Rb8 e4 47. Kb5 Rd6 48. a6 Kd7 49. Rg8 Ke6 50. Re8+ Kf5
51. Rb8 Re6 52. Rb7 Ra8 53. a7 e3 54. Rxg7 e2 55. Re1 Kf4 56. Rg3 Re3 57. Kb6
Rxg3 58. hxg3+ Ke3 59. Kb7 Rxa7+ 0-1

