{The following fragment is also quite instructive. Contrary to the previous
example, instead of 13.Ne5, White opted for the solid} 13. Qe2 {Black, however,
executed exactly the same exchange operation as in the previous game -} cxd4
14. exd4 Ba3 {As we know, by exchanging the dark-squared bishops Black
drastically reduces White's attacking potential. For example, we will no
longer fear the advance d4-d5.} 15. Ne5 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Rab8 {Once again, Black
builds his play on the advance ...b6-b5.} ({In general, the structural
transformation} 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 {is favourable for Black unless White
has something concrete which is not the case here. Black will obtain a huge
advantage with simple moves such as ...Bc6 followed by ...Nc5 and ...Rad8. The
move} 18. Nxb6 {is well met by the elegant} Nc5 {[%cal Ga8d8] followed by ...
Rad8 with more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 17. Rfe1 Nxe5 {Black
gladly keeps exchanging pieces.} 18. Rxe5 Ng4 {The most active possibility.
Black is already planning to follow with ...Qh4. Therefore, White played} 19.
Rh5 g6 20. Rh3 Qg5 {Black is now ready to increase the pressure on White's
centre by playing ...Qf4. At the same time, the thematic ...b6-b5 is always on
the air.} 21. Bf1 Qf4 22. Rd1 b5 {Finally, Black executes his thematic idea.} (
{According to the computer, even more precise would have been} 22... Bc6 23.
Nc3 b5 {when Black's better structure gives him a positional advantage.}) 23.
cxb5 axb5 24. Nc5 Bc6 $132 {The c5-knight is not doing much. Practically
speaking, Black's play is easier since White should play dynamically in order
to compensate for the inferior structure.} 25. Nd3 Qd6 26. Be2 Nf6 27. Ne5 Bd5
28. Qd2 Rfc8 29. Qg5 Qd8 30. Bd3 Nd7 31. Qh6 Nf8 32. Qf4 Rb7 33. a3 Rcc7 34.
Ng4 f5 35. Ne5 b4 36. axb4 Rxb4 37. Rg3 Rg7 38. h4 Bb3 39. Nc6 Qb6 40. Rc1 Ra4
41. Qd6 Qc7 42. Qxc7 Rxc7 43. Bb5 Rb4 44. Rc5 Rxb5 45. Rxb5 Ba4 46. Ra5 Bxc6
47. Rc3 Nd7 48. Ra6 Nb8 49. Ra8 Rc8 50. Rxc6 1/2-1/2

