{In the next game, we will see how to handle the structure arising in the line
4.Nc3 Bb7 5.Bg5. My opponent GM Halkias is known to be an expert in this line.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. Bg5 {[%cal Ge2e3] This is one of
White's most solid systems against Queen's Indian Defence. For the time being,
White is planning to just develop his pieces as quickly as possible. If Black
plays ...d7-d5, we reach a famous position from Queen's Gambit Declined. In
this game, I employed the setup that I consider most sensible.} Be7 6. e3 ({
Sometimes, White might start with} 6. Qc2 {Nevertheless, for our setup, the
exact move order is not that important.}) 6... h6 {In the next moves, it will
become clear why it's useful to force the white bishop to h4.} 7. Bh4 O-O ({
In this concrete move order, Black can also play} 7... Ne4 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 {
getting a structure that we covered when dealing with the Petrosian System.
Nevertheless, White could have avoided this option by starting with 6.Qc2.}) 8.
Qc2 {This is the most popular move.} ({Another important system is} 8. Bd3 {
Just like after 8.Qc2, I suggest attacking the centre with} c5 9. O-O ({After} 
9. dxc5 bxc5 {, we get the structure from the main line.}) 9... cxd4 10. exd4 (
{After} 10. Nxd4 a6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd7d6,Gb8d7] the arising Hedgehog structure
is favourable for Black since White's setup is a bit passive.}) {At this point,
my favourite idea is} 10... Bxf3 $5 ({Obviously, there is nothing wrong with
the traditional} 10... d5) {Black's point becomes clear after} 11. Qxf3 Nc6 {
[%csl Rd4,Rh4] It turns out that White does not have a comfortable way of
covering the d4-pawn. You can now see the point of the inclusion 6...h6 7.Bh4.
Had the white bishop been on g5, the move Be3 would have been possible. In
this position, White has nothing better than} 12. Ne2 ({In my online games, I
often face} 12. d5 $6 {which is dubious in view of} Ne5 13. Qe2 Nxd3 14. Qxd3
Nxd5 {Black is temporarily winning a pawn. Of course, White can restore the
material equality by means of} 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Rad1 Ng6 17. Qxd7 {
Nevertheless, in the endgame arising after} Qxd7 18. Rxd7 Ne5 19. Rd4 Rfd8 20.
Rfd1 Rxd4 21. Rxd4 Rc8 22. b3 g5 $15 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7] Black can still rely
on a slight advantage. After bringing the king to e7, he can start gaining
space on the kingside. At the same time, White cannot advance his queenside
pawns. Additionally, in some cases, White should reckon with the idea ...a7-a6
followed by ...b6-b5.}) 12... d5 {After forcing the white knight into the
passive e2-square, Black immediately strikes in the centre.} 13. Rad1 Nb4 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. cxd5 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (56) Giri, A 
(2772) -Ponkratov, P (2641) Warsaw 2021. At this point, Black could have played
} Nxd5 $11 {with a comfortable equality.}) 8... c5 9. dxc5 bxc5 {We have
already examined a similar structure when dealing with the Fianchetto
variation. Compared to the g2-g3 systems, this version is slightly more
favourable for White since he can put pressure on d6 by putting the
dark-squared bishop on g3. Of course, in order to increase the pressure, White
is going to double the rooks on the d-file. On the other hand, Black has
enough resources to protect the pawn. After stabilizing the position, he will
start considering the advance ...d6-d5. The next few moves are quite logical.}
10. Be2 d6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rfd1 Qb6 13. Rd2 Rfd8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,
Gf8g6] It's important to put exactly this rook on d8. In this way, Black makes
the f8-square available for the knight. Ideally, the knight will go to g6
while the rooks will be doubled on d-file.} 14. Rad1 a6 {This prophylactic
move is designed to cover the b5-square. Sooner or later, Black should play it.
} ({Another model game for this structure saw the immediate} 14... Nf8 15. h3 {
By means of this thematic move, white frees the h2-square for the bishop,
anticipating 15...Ng6 16.Bg3 Nh5.} Rd7 16. Ne1 {[%cal Ge2f3] Another thematic
move. In this structure, White usually exchanges his passive light-squared
bishop via the f3-square.} Rad8 17. Bf3 Ng6 18. Bg3 Bc6 {Obviously, Black is
not going to activate White's knight by taking on f3. With his last move, he
frees the b7-square for the queen.} 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Nf3 a6 21. Bh2 {White
managed to improve his position to the maximum. Since he has no more
constructive ideas, he starts making waiting moves. If Black wants to play for
a win, he should carry out the advance ...d6-d5 in a favourable way.} Rb8 {
By speculating with the idea of ...Rb4, Jobava is trying to induce the advance
b2-b3. Only after that, he will prepare ...d6-d5. The idea is that in some
lines the c3-knight might prove unstable.} 22. b3 Rbd8 23. Qd3 d5 {Everything
is ready for this advance!} 24. cxd5 exd5 25. Qf5 $2 {This move is already a
decisive mistake.} ({More logical would have been} 25. Ne5 {When playing
against hanging pawns, we try to exchange pieces. A possible continuation
would be} Nxe5 26. Bxe5 Qe6 27. Bxf6 Bxf6 28. Qc2 a5 $132 {The advance ...
a6-a5 is always useful in such positions. Besides gaining queenside space,
Black rules out any b3-b4 ideas. The position remains balanced.}) 25... d4 $1 {
Black delivers this thematic break under perfect circumstances.} 26. exd4 cxd4
{[%csl Rc3] We can now see the point behind 21...Rb8. The entire operation
works due to the vulnerable c3-knight.} 27. Na4 d3 $1 {One more important move.
The d3-pawn is untouchable due to the back rank weakness.} 28. Nb2 Rd5 $6 {
This is a slight inaccuracy.} ({After} 28... Bb4 29. Rxd3 Rxd3 30. Nxd3 Qc2 $19
{Black is winning on the spot.}) 29. Ne5 $4 {This is losing immediately.} ({
More tenacious would have been} 29. Be5 {Even in this case, however, after} Nd7
30. Nxd3 Qb5 $19 {Black has a decisive advantage.}) 29... Rxe5 {0-1 (29)
Yakovich,Y (2600) -Jobava,B (2658) Sochi 2007. White resigned in view of} 30.
Bxe5 Nh4 $19) 15. Bg3 Nf8 16. Ne1 Rd7 17. Bf3 Rad8 {I have played this
standard move without too much thinking.} ({Given the fact White didn't play
h2-h3, I could have played} 17... Bxf3 18. Nxf3 Nh5 {Now, White cannot save
his bishop from an exchange. The jump} 19. Ne5 {does not create any problems.
Black can play} Rdd8 20. Nd3 Nxg3 21. hxg3 Nd7 {[%cal Gb6c6,Gd7f6] followed by
...Nf6 and ...Qc6. Black has nothing to worry about.}) 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. Nf3
Ng6 20. h3 d5 {Black is perfectly ready for this central break.} ({It goes
without saying that Black can keep making waiting moves. For example, after} 
20... Nh5 21. Bh2 Nf6 {it's not clear how White will improve his position.})
21. cxd5 Nxd5 {This idea of this move is to free the f6-square for the bishop.
On the other hand, exchanges of minor pieces are generally favourable for
White.} ({Slightly more precise would have been} 21... exd5 $132 {with a
decent version of hanging pawns. The structure is quite similar to the game of
Jobava.}) 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. b3 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gh4h5] Without the knight on f6,
Black should already reckon with the advance h3-h4-h5. At this point, I played}
Qb5 {[%cal Ge7f6] protecting the c5-pawn and preparing ...Bf6.} ({More precise
would have been} 23... Qb6 {The the following line is a good illustration of
Black's dynamic potential.} 24. h4 h5 25. Qf5 Qe6 $1 {The main reason behind
23...Qb6. The point is that} 26. Qxh5 {will be answered with} d4 27. exd4 Rd5
$1 {Thanks to this intermediate move, Black's entire concept works.} 28. Ng5
Bxg5 29. hxg5 cxd4 $132 {The powerful central passer gives Black enough
counterplay.}) 24. h4 Bf6 25. h5 Nf8 26. Be5 Nh7 27. Rc1 Be7 {Even though
there is nothing wrong with this move, Black could have played more
energetically.} ({The advance} 27... d4 $1 {would have been the optimal
solution. Once again, we see the dynamic potential of the hanging pawns.} 28.
exd4 ({After} 28. Qxc5 $2 dxe3 $1 {White is already worse.} 29. Rxd7 ({The
problem is that} 29. Qxb5 $2 {is well met by the intermediate} exd2 $19 {
when Black is winning.}) 29... exf2+ 30. Kxf2 Qxd7 $17 {Black has a huge
advantage due to the vulnerable white king.}) 28... cxd4 29. a4 Qb4 30. Bxf6
Nxf6 31. Ne5 Rd6 $132 {Once again, the central passed pawn provides Black with
decent dynamic resources. Additionally, the h5-pawn is a target.}) 28. Bb2 a5
$4 {This is a blunder.} ({After} 28... Ng5 {Black has nothing to worry about.})
29. Ne5 Ng5 {I was forced to sacrifice an exchange. When considering 28...a5,
I have missed that any rook move can be met by Nxf7.} 30. Nxd7 Qxd7 31. Qd1 Qf5
32. Qe2 Bd6 33. Rdc2 Re8 34. Rxc5 Re4 35. Rc8+ Kh7 {In this position, White
played} 36. R8c6 {and offered a draw since he considered the position arising
after 36...Rg4 to be unclear.} ({Instead, after} 36. Rd8 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc1c8]
White is winning since all the tactics work in his favour. The threat is Rcc8
on the next move.}) 1/2-1/2

