{ In this game we will start dealing
with the typical structures that might arise in the so-called Miles System - 1.
d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 b6 4.Bf4. In this example, Black shows how to play
against the doubled pawns on c3 and c4.} 1. d4 e6 ({The Queen's Indian move
order is} 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 Bb4+ $1 {It's very
important to start with this check, The idea is to force the b1-knight into
the passive d2-square. The drawback of this move is that White will have to
play with doubled pawns on c3 and c4.} 6. Nc3 ({The main point behind 5...Bb4
is that after provoking} 6. Nbd2 {Black can play} Be7 {[%cal Gc7c5] followed
by ...c7-c5. Of course, with the white knight being on c3, the advance ...
c7-c5 will be met by d4-d5.}) ({The most challenging continuation is} 6. Nfd2 {
[%cal Ga2a3,Gb1c3] with the idea a2-a3 followed by Nc3. We will deal with this
move a bit later.}) 6... Ne4 {Black is not in a hurry to take on c3.
Beforehand, he wants to fortify his knight on e4.} 7. Qc2 O-O 8. Bd3 f5 9. O-O
Bxc3 10. bxc3 d6 {We have already reached the position from the game.}) 2. c4
b6 3. Nf3 Bb7 4. Qc2 f5 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bb4 7. e3 Ne4 8. Bd3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
O-O 10. O-O d6 {We have a typical structure that might also arise form
Nimzo-Indian and Bogo-Indian. In such cases, White usually goes for a central
activity in order to compensate for his damaged pawn structure. It's obvious
that such a strategy does not work in this position since Black established a
firm blockade on e4. When Black exchanges his dark-squared bishop for the
c3-knight, he usually tries to apply the so-called light-square strategy. The
explanation is simple. For example, in this position, all the three black
minor pieces control the light squares. At the same time, White can control
the light squares with only two pieces. Black's main strategy is to exchange a
pair of knights, as well as the light-squared bishops. In such a scenario,
White will be left with his useless dark-squared bishop. In a position with
queen + knight vs queen + dark-squared bishop, White will not be able to
neutralize Black's play on the light squares. The most logical continuation.
White immediately starts fighting for the e4-square. On the other hand,
exchanging a pair of knights is also part of Black's plan.} 11. Nd2 ({In this
structure, you should always calculate the break} 11. c5 {This move often
allows White to unbalance the position, even at the price of a pawn sacrifice.
In this concrete position, Black manages to coordinate his forces. The
following sequence is a good illustration.} bxc5 12. Qb3 Qc8 13. Bc4 Re8 14.
Rfb1 Bc6 $15 {Black managed to protect everything. It's clear that White does
not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Nd7 {[%cal
Ge6e5] Black is already preparing the thematic advance ...e6-e5. The next few
moves are quite logical -} 13. f3 e5 14. Bg3 Qe7 15. Rae1 Rae8 16. Qc2 g6 {
This is not the most precise continuation.} ({Black should have applied his
light-square strategy by playing} 16... e4 $1 {practically forcing the
favourable exchange of the light-squared bishops.} 17. fxe4 ({After} 17. Be2
exf3 18. Bxf3 Bxf3 19. Rxf3 Qe4 20. Qxe4 Rxe4 $17 {Black has a huge advantage
due to his better structure and domination on the light squares. White's
bishop is completely useless.}) 17... Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 {Once again, Black
enjoys a classical advantage.}) 17. f4 e4 18. Be2 Nb8 19. Rb1 Nc6 20. Qd2 Na5
21. Qe1 Ba6 22. Bh4 Qd7 23. Rb4 c5 24. Rb5 Bxb5 25. cxb5 cxd4 26. cxd4 Rc8 27.
g4 Nc4 28. Qg3 Nd2 29. Rf2 Nf3+ 30. Bxf3 exf3 31. Qxf3 d5 32. h3 Rc3 33. Rg2
Qxb5 34. gxf5 Rxf5 35. Bf2 Rc1+ 36. Kh2 Qb1 37. Qg4 Rh1+ 38. Kg3 Qe4 39. Qh4
Kg7 40. Qd8 Qe6 41. Rh2 Rxh2 42. Kxh2 Rf8 43. Qc7+ Rf7 44. Qd8 Qd7 45. Qb8 Qc7
46. Qa8 Qd6 47. h4 Rc7 48. Qb8 Rd7 49. Qe8 Rd8 50. Qa4 Qd7 51. Qb3 Rc8 52. e4
dxe4 53. d5 Qg4 54. Qb2+ Kh6 55. Qd2 Qf5 56. d6 Rd8 57. Be3 Rd7 58. a4 Qg4 59.
Bf2 Kg7 60. Qd4+ Kf7 61. Bg3 Qf5 62. Be1 Ke6 63. Bb4 a5 64. Ba3 Qxf4+ 0-1

