{Now, it's time to take a look at White's most challenging ways to play the
Miles System.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 Bb4+ 6. Nfd2 {
This is by far the main move. White is planning to follow with a2-a3 and Nc3.
Additionally, in some cases, the f3-square can be used for the bishop. The
drawback is that the move 6.Nfd2 reduces White's central control.} ({As I have
pointed out in my annotations to the previous example, after} 6. Nbd2 {Black
should play} Be7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gf6h5] Preparing the break ...c7-c5. At the same
time, White should already reckon with the idea of ...Nh5. White's most
natural reaction is} 7. h3 ({Another high-profile game saw} 7. Bd3 Nh5 8. O-O
Nxf4 9. exf4 O-O $15 {Black's flexible structure makes the bishop pair a
significant factor in this position. In the future, Black will try to open up
the position by means of the breaks ...c7-c5 and ...d7-d5.0-1 (29) Vovk, Y 
(2611) -Neiksans, A (2607) Fagernes 2016}) 7... c5 {With the white knight on
c3, instead of d2, this break wouldn't have been possible in view of d4-d5.} 8.
Be2 cxd4 {After this move, Black gets a very decent version of the Hedgehog
structure.} 9. Nxd4 ({In case of} 9. exd4 O-O 10. O-O d5 $15 {Black is already
slightly better. With bishop on f4 and knight on d2, White is not well
prepared for IQP structure.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O a6 {This is the way to go if
you want to play in a classical Hedgehog fashion.} ({Another decent
alternative is} 10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 $11 {with full equality. Black can
already simplify with ...d7-d5. On the other hand, if he wants to fight for a
win, playing in the Hedgehog style is still an option. Without the knight on
d4, it will be even easier to execute the break ...b6-b5.}) 11. Rc1 d6 12. Bh2
Nbd7 $132 {Black has nothing to worry about. Compared to the usual Hedgehog
positions, White's setup is very passive.}) 6... O-O 7. a3 Bd6 $5 {In my
opinion, this rare move is the simplest way to solve the problems.} ({The
traditional main line is} 7... Be7 {One of the ideas behind the Miles System
is well illustrated by the following typical line -} 8. Nc3 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10.
Be2 c5 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Bf3 {It turns out that White is very well prepared to
put pressure on the hanging pawns. Even though the position remains balanced,
Black should handle it with care.}) 8. Bg3 {This is by far the most
challenging continuation. White is ready to exchange the bishop only if he can
open the h-file.} ({It's also very important to understand the structure
arising after} 8. Bxd6 cxd6 9. Nc3 d5 {If White just allows the exchange of
the central pawns, without getting something in return, the arising
symmetrical structure is pretty harmless for Black. The most challenging
continuation is} 10. Qf3 {preventing Black from activating his problematic
bishop. Additionally, White creates the threat of 11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Bc4.
Fortunately, I found a new idea that immediately solves all the problems.} ({
The alternative} 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Qf3 {is less challenging since Black can
support the d5-knight by means of the manoeuvre...Na6-c7.} ({A move such as} 
11. Nde4 {is totally harmless. One of the many ways leading to equality is}
Nxc3 12. Nxc3 Na6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ga6c7,Gd8g5] Black is ready to provoke further
simplifications by means of the manoeuvre...Na6-c7-d5. It's important to
remember that, with a pawn on d7, the advance ...f7-f5 followed by kingside
activity is quite a valid option. A possible follow-up would be} 13. Qg4 f5 14.
Qg3 Nc7 15. Bd3 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {Black has nothing to worry about. In
many cases, he is even ready to display activity by means of the manoeuvre...
Rf6-g6.}) 11... Na6 12. Bc4 {The most active continuation.} ({In case of} 12.
Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qh5 Nc7 14. Bd3 f5 15. O-O {Black can execute a typical idea -}
Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8f6] Remember the maneuver ...Nb8-a6-c7-e8-f6. In this
structure, the knight is very well placed on f6. After} 16. Qe2 Qg5 17. f3 Nf6
$132 {Black enjoys a decent counterplay.}) 12... Nac7 13. O-O Rb8 {It's clear
that White cannot make use of the pin. After} 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Rac1 Rc8 $11 {
[%cal Gf7f5] The position is completely equal. Black is ready to follow with ..
.f7-f5.}) 10... Nc6 $1 $146 {This novelty appears to be very strong. Black
temporarily sacrifices a pawn in order to complete the development and
coordinate his pieces. White cannot speculate with the central tension any
longer.} 11. cxd5 Ne7 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gf7f5] This is the point. If allowed, Black
will take on d5 with the f6-knight and will follow with ...f7-f5. White's only
way to fight for an advantage is} 12. e4 exd5 13. e5 {In this case, Black
solves all the problems with the energetic} Ne4 14. Ndxe4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 d6 {
Black's development and piece activity provide enough compensation for the
sacrificed material. The following sequence is quite illustrative -} 16. exd6
Nf5 17. O-O-O Nxd6 18. d5 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Re8 20. Qd4 Qg5+ 21. f4 ({Of course,
White can give the pawn back by playing} 21. Kb1 {In this case, Black's most
logical reaction will be} Rad8 22. Bc4 Qxg2 23. Rhe1 Qg6+ 24. Ka1 Qd6 $132 {
Black managed to safely block the passed pawn. Exchanges on the e-file will
obviously happen. The position is balanced.}) 21... Rac8+ 22. Kb1 Qf5+ 23. Bd3
({The alternative} 23. Ka1 {is well met by} Bxd5 $132 {The point is that Qxd5
will be answered with ...Rc1+ followed by ...Qb1+.}) 23... Qxd5 24. Qxd5 Bxd5
25. Bxh7+ Kxh7 26. Rxd5 Re2 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) ({Another game of
Eljanov saw} 8. Bg5 {At the point, Black reacted in a very precise way -} h6 9.
Bh4 Be7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This position reminds the system with 4.Nc3 and 5.Bg5.
In this case, however, instead of Nc3, White played the completely useless
Nfd2. The extra a2-a3 move does not help at all. Black is ready to execute the
thematic break ...c7-c5.} 10. Nc3 c5 11. Nf3 cxd4 12. exd4 d5 {Given the fact
that White is not well developed, Black will gladly accept a position with IQP.
} 13. Bxf6 $2 {This exchange allows Black to increase his pressure on d4.} ({
Black's reaction to} 13. Bd3 {is very instructive -} Nc6 14. O-O dxc4 15. Bxc4
Nh5 {Remember this thematic move in positions with IQP. This exchange
operation wouldn't have been possible without the inclusion of the moves 8...
h6 9.Bh4. Had the bishop been on g5, at this point, White could have played 16.
Be3.} 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%cal Gh5f6,Gd8d6] After the exchange of the dark-squared
bishops, White does not have any attacking chances. Black is ready to proceed
with ...Nf6 followed by ...Qd6 and ...Rfd8, thus increasing the pressure on d4.
}) 13... Bxf6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black obtained an
winning advantage. He is ready to increase the pressure by means of ...Nc6.1/
2-1/2 (58) Livaic,L (2507) -Eljanov,P (2672) Chess.com INT 2020}) {After
submitting this position to extensive analysis, I have reached the conclusion
that} 8... Bxg3 $1 {is the most precise continuation.} ({In the game Eljanov
played} 8... h6 {which is less good. At this point, instead of 9.Nxc3, White
could have played} 9. Bxd6 cxd6 10. Rg1 d5 11. g4 $36 {This is quite a
sensible approach. White is planning to use the h6-pawn as a hook. At least
practically speaking, Black's play is not comfortable.}) 9. hxg3 c5 {Since
White is planning to develop a kingside attack, Black should immediately
strike in the centre.} 10. g4 {The most principled choice.} ({In case of} 10.
Bd3 {Black can play either} h6 ({or} 10... g6 {with a comfortable position in
both cases.})) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 ({The ultra-aggressive} 11. g5 {leads to a
forced draw after} dxe3 12. fxe3 Ne4 13. Bd3 Qxg5 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Nxe4 Qxe3+
16. Qe2 Qc1+ 17. Qd1 Qe3+ $11) 11... h6 12. Nc3 Nh7 $1 {In my opinion, this
strong prophylactic move is the simplest way of neutralizing White's kingside
activity. Black is now ready to attack White's centre with ...Nc6.} 13. Bd3 Nc6
14. Bxh7+ {This move is the most sensible try to justify the previous
aggressive play. A logical sequence would be} Kxh7 15. d5 Ne5 16. Qe2 exd5 17.
cxd5 a5 18. O-O-O d6 19. Nde4 {White's attacking concept is based on the
advance g4-g5. Fortunately, Black has an elegant solution at his disposal -}
Nxg4 20. Qxg4 f5 21. Qe2 fxe4 22. Qxe4+ Kg8 $132 {Black has very decent
counterplay in this position. He can already consider transferring the bishop
to f5. White's king is already more vulnerable.} 1-0

