{In the theoretical section, I explain the most important systems that are not
covered in the sections dedicated to the different pawn structures. Even
though I tried to provide extensive theoretical coverage, some minor lines
might be still missing. If you know all the typical pawn structures, that
wouldn't be a problem. When possible, I have always tried to base my analysis
on familiar structures. In the analysis, you will find many new ideas and
concepts. After studying the material, you will have GM knowledge of the
Queen's Indian theory. Enjoy!}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queen's Indian"]
[Black "7.d5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E17"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "44"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.04.15"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. d5 {This is
probably the most concrete variation in our entire Queen's Indian repertoire.
White is sacrificing a pawn in order to develop a dangerous initiative. During
a long period of time, the move 7.d5 was out of fashion. In 2018, however,
AlphaZero played it in the famous match against Stockfish, thus provoking a
new spike in the popularity of this line. White's main idea is to answer} exd5
{with} 8. Nh4 {[%cal Gc4d5] White's positional idea is to play cxd5 on the
next move. In this case, he will get a strategically winning position due to
the tremendous space advantage.} ({An important alternative is} 8. Nd4 {
when White has pretty much the same idea. The knight will eventually go to f5
as in the main line. In this case, however, I suggest the rare} Nc6 $5 {
This move allows Black to play for a win in a strategically complicated
position.} ({In most of the cases, the move} 8... c6 {transposes to the main
line.}) 9. cxd5 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bc5 $5 {This move has been tried in only one
game. Black's first priority is to activate the bishop. Only afterwards, he
will decide whether to play ... d7-d6 or attack the centre by means of ...
c7-c6.} ({Black's usual choice is} 10... c5 {when after} 11. Qd3 d6 12. Nc3 {
White enjoys a favourable version of Modern Benoni. The bishop is clearly
misplaced on b7. At the same time, the dark-squared bishop would have been
better placed on the long diagonal.}) 11. Qd3 {This is the more natural
continuation.} ({An obvious alternative is} 11. Qd1 {In this case, Black
should start preparing the break ...c7-c6.} Re8 12. Nc3 h6 {The inclusion of
this move is important. Otherwise, White can answer .. .c7-c6 with Bg5. At
this point, I have examined several options for White. Don't try to memorize
the variations. My analysis are designed to illustrate the logic of the battle
in such structures.} 13. b3 {To my understanding, this is the most natural
continuation.} ({In case of} 13. e4 {In order not to find himself in a very
passive position, Black should immediately strike with} c6 14. Bf4 ({The
advance} 14. d6 {should be always considered. Black's typical reaction is} Re6
15. Bf4 ({Note that after} 15. Bh3 {instead of spoiling his coordination by
taking the d6-pawn, Black can sacrifice an exchange by playing} Qe8 $1 16. Bxe6
Qxe6 $17 {Black has an obvious advantage since the d6-pawn is doomed. Besides,
in the long run, White will feel the absence of his light-squared bishop.})
15... g5 16. Be3 Rxd6 17. Qf3 Re6 $132 {Even though the position remains very
complicated, I don't think that White has full compensation for the pawn.})
14... d6 {[%cal Gc6d5] After ...cxd5, Black would get an easy plan. Afterwards,
he can follow with ...Qd7 and ...b6-b5-b4. White can try to challenge the
c5-bishop by means of} 15. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Even though not completely forced,
the following line shows the dynamic potential of the position.} cxd5 (15... a5
$5 {is playable as well.}) 16. b4 d4 17. Nd5 Nxe4 18. Qb3 Qd7 $1 19. Rae1 ({
It turns out that after} 19. bxc5 $4 Qe6 20. Bxe4 Qxe4 21. Rae1 Bxd5 22. Rxe4
Bxb3 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. cxd6 d3 $17 {Black is almost winning.}) 19... Ng5 20.
bxc5 dxc5 21. Bxg5 hxg5 22. Qf3 Rad8 23. Nf6+ gxf6 24. Qxf6 Bxg2 25. Qxg5+ Kh7
26. Qh5+ $11) ({After} 13. Bf4 {Black will answer with the natural} c6 14. a3 {
