Black should take with the bishop. As we know, taking with the pawn gives
White a slight structural advantage. The simplifications arising after} 10.
Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Ne5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 c5 13. dxc5 Qc7 14. Nd3 Qb7+ 15. f3 bxc5 $11 {
lead to an equal position. The c5-pawn is not that weak as it might seem.
Black has good central control and can consider putting pressure on the b-file.
}) ({An interesting waiting move is} 8. h4 $5 {Besides gaining space on the
kingside, White also secures the f4-square for the bishop. In my opinion,
Black's simplest solution is} f5 9. Ng5 {Otherwise, the move h2-h4 has no
point.} h6 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Nc3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8f7]
Black has decent counterplay in this position. In my opinion, the move h2-h4
made the kingside vulnerable. An interesting idea for Black is to transfer the
queen to f7. After that, it's possible to prepare the advance ...e6-e5.}) 8...
d5 {Whenever White plays Nfd2, the advance ...d7-d5 is a decent option.} ({
In this case,} 8... f5 {is dubious in view of} 9. d5 Nc5 10. Nc3 $16 {with a
huge advantage for White.}) 9. Nc3 {The most natural move.} ({To transposition
leads} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 ({or} 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nc3 f5)) ({An independent
direction is} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nc3 f5 11. f3 {White puts maximum pressure on
e4. On the other hand, Black obtains sufficient counterplay by putting
pressure on d4 -} Bf6 ({Of course, White's dream is} 11... exf3 12. exf3 {
[%csl Re6][%cal Ge1e6] with terrible pressure on e6. In this case, 7.Re1 comes
in handy.}) 12. Be3 Nc6 {Another nice application of the concept ...Bf6 + ...
Nc6. The next few moves are logical and forced.} 13. fxe4 Bxd4 14. Bxd4 Qxd4+
15. Qxd4 Nxd4 16. Rac1 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Rad8 {The position is equal. 1/2 Volkov,S
(2579) -Abasov,N (2531) /Konya TUR 2014 (31)}) 9... f5 10. cxd5 {In order to
fight for an advantage, White must open the c-file.} ({After} 10. Ndxe4 dxe4
11. f3 Bf6 12. Be3 Nc6 13. fxe4 Bxd4 $132 {we have a transposition to 9.Nxe4.})
10... exd5 11. Ndxe4 dxe4 {Taking with the d-pawn is very important. In this
way, Black has the possibility of putting pressure on d4.} 12. Bf4 {[%cal
Ga1c1] This is the critical position of the entire system. White is planning
to put pressure on the c-file by means of Rc1.} Nc6 {Even though 12...Bd6 is
possible as well, I find this continuation more straightforward.} 13. Nb5 ({
White can also start with} 13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Rad1 ({In case of} 14. e3 {the
simplest solution would be} Bd6 {when after} 15. Bxd6 cxd6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gd6d5]
we get a thematic structure for this variation. Black is ready to proceed with
...Ne7 followed by ...d6-d5. Unless White has something very concrete, this
structure is always comfortable for Black. A possible follow-up would be} 16.
Rac1 Ne7 17. h4 d5 18. Ne2 Qd6 19. Bf1 g6 $11 {with equality.}) 14... Bd6 15.
Bxd6 {Once again, we get the same structure. White can try to prevent Black
from playing the thematic ...Ne7 followed by ... d6-d5 by means of} cxd6 {
[%cal Gc6e7,Gd6d5]} 16. d5 Ne7 17. f3 {Nevertheless, after} exf3 18. exf3 f4
$132 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gg6e5] Black has decent counterplay on the kingside. The
maneuver ...Ng6-e5 already comes into consideration.}) ({One of the most
critical tries is} 13. d5 Nb4 14. d6 Bxd6 15. Qb3+ {This position was reached
in the game Nikolov,M - Ozturk, E, 2017. Now, instead of 15...Kh8, Black
should have played} Rf7 16. Rad1 Na6 {Black is ready to give the pawn back in
order to neutralize White's initiative. The following line is quite
illustrative -} 17. Bxd6 cxd6 18. Qe6 Nc5 19. Qxd6 Qe8 20. b4 Ne6 21. Qe5 Nc7
22. Qxe8+ Rxe8 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gc7e6,Gf7c7,Gg7g6,Gg8g7,Gg7f6,Gf6e5] Black has
nothing to worry about. If White is not precise enough, Black can even get
slightly better due to his space advantage.}) ({Of course,} 13. e3 {is well
met by} Bd6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 {when we get the structure we are looking for.})
13... Bd6 14. Nxd6 cxd6 {We have reached the same thematic structure but with
one significant difference - white has a bishop pair. For the time being, both
bishops are well neutralized. With a bishop of f4, however, Black should
refrain from ...d6-d5. Instead, it's possible to use the d5-square for the
knight.} 15. Rc1 h6 16. Qa4 Ne7 17. Qa3 Rf6 $11 {Black is ready to follow with
...Nd5. In my opinion, Black's play is even easier.} *

