1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2
Bf6 9. Re1 {This move is one of White's recent tries in the fight for an
advantage. In many variations, the rook turns out to be very useful on e1. In
my opinion, Black should settle for the Benoni approach by means of} c5 ({
One of the ideas behind 9.Re1 can be seen after} 9... d6 10. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 ({
White's idea is that} 10... Nxc3 $6 {will be answered with} 11. Qc2 {With the
white rook on f1, instead of e1, Black would have just taken on e2 with a
check. Now, he is forced to go for} Bxg5 12. Bxb7 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 Ne4 14. Qc2 $16
{when White is going to win an exchange.}) 11. Bxg5 Qxg5 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4
{White was slightly better in the game 1-0 (56) Gelfand, B (2673) -Esipenko, A
(2593) Moscow 2018}) 10. d5 {Usually, we get this position when the move Rc1
has been played, instead of Re1. Since this is a significant difference, Black
shouldn't play automatically.} Bxc3 {[%csl Re1,Ge4] This is the concept that I
am going to advocate here. Black leaves his knight on e4 in order to prevent
any e2-e4 ideas.} ({The standard} 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 d6 {
does not work quite well here. For example, after} 13. Nde4 {our usual line
with} Be5 {does not work quite well here. White can just play} 14. f4 Bd4+ 15.
e3 {Once again, we see the usefulness of the e1-rook. In the normal lines with
Rc1, this move wouldn't have been possible. The position arising after} Bxc3
16. Nxc3 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5] is very difficult for Black. White is ready to
start a powerful central expansion by means of e3-e4-e5.}) 11. Bxc3 d6 12. Qc2
{The most natural move. White should fight against the centralized knight.} ({
The Nimzo-Indian type of structure arising after} 12. Nd2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 e5 {
is totally fine for Black.}) 12... Nxc3 {This move marks the beginning of a
forced sequence -} 13. Qxc3 exd5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Qd3 Bc6 16. Rad1 {This
position has been reached in two games. In both cases, Black played ...d6-d5.
My suggestion is} Re8 {Giving the pawn back in order to estiguish White's
initiative.} 17. Qxd6 ({After} 17. e4 Bb7 18. Nh4 ({Another attempt would be} 
18. e5 d5 19. Nh4 Qd7 20. Qf3 (20. Nf5 Nc6) 20... g6 21. Rxd5 Bxd5 22. Qxd5
Qxd5 23. Bxd5 Nd7 24. Bxa8 Rxa8 $11 {with equality.}) 18... g6 $11 19. Qxd6
Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Na6 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ga6b4] Black has decent counterplay.}) 17...
Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Be4 $11 {Black managed to solve all his problems. He is ready to
follow with ...Nc6 and ...Rad8.} *

