1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2
Bf6 9. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] We have already discussed this sysem in the section
dedicated to the typical structures arising in the system with 4.g3. Now, we
will just expand our theoretical background.} ({After} 9. Be1 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Be4
11. Ne5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 {we just transpose to the main line.}) 9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3
Bxg2 11. Kxg2 c5 12. dxc5 {The most common reply. As we know, however, the
so-called dxc5 ...bxc5 structure is almost always favourable for Black.} ({
In case of} 12. Nf3 cxd4 {we get a Hedgehog structure that is harmless for
Black.} 13. Bxd4 ({In case of} 13. Nxd4 {the most precise reaction is} d5 14.
cxd5 Qxd5+ 15. Nf3 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Na6 $11 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black is
even on the bright side of the equality in view of the vulnerable c3-pawn.})
13... Be7 14. Qd3 d6 $11 {This harmless for Black version of the Hedgehog was
reached in the game 1/2 (43) Aronian, L (2809) -Grischuk, A (2764) London 2013}
) ({In the section featuring the typical pawn structures, we have already
analyzed the position arising after} 12. Ng4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Nc6
15. Qd6 Qg5 16. Ne3 {When examining this version of the Hedgehog structure, we
mostly focused on the idea ...Rfd8 followed by ...Qc5. You can check my
annotations to the model game Hammer - Eljanov. Now, I would like to present a
bit more aggressive concept -} Rad8 17. Rfd1 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] Black
immediately goes for a kingside activity. The advance ...f5-f4 is coming.
Therefore, White should play} 18. f4 {Nevertheless, after} Qf6 19. Rd2 g5 {
It transpires that the white king is not safe at all. Black is planning to
open the g-file.} 20. Kh1 gxf4 21. gxf4 Kh8 22. Rg1 Rg8 $132 {Black got decent
counterplay in the game 1/2 (39) Erdos,V (2624) -Eljanov,P (2720) Antalya 2017}
) ({In case of} 12. d5 d6 13. Ng4 Bxc3 14. bxc3 h5 15. Ne3 e5 $132 {Black is
doing very well. He can already consider displaying a kingside activity with ..
.f7-f5 and ...h5-h4.}) 12... bxc5 13. Qd6 Be7 {This is the most ambitious way
of handling the position.} ({We already know that after} 13... Qb6 14. Rfd1
Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Be7 16. Rd2 d6 $11 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 14. Qd3 {
The most critical try. White's idea is to answer ...d7-d6 with 15.Qf3.
Therefore, Black should start with} f6 ({Wasting time for} 14... a5 {is not a
good option because White can start gaining space on the kingside by means of}
15. f4 {After} d6 16. Ng4 {Black's position is already unpleasant since the
threat of f4-f5-f6 is quite annoying.}) (14... d6 $2 15. Qf3 $16) 15. Nf3 ({
The tactical justification behind 14...f6 can be seen in the following
variation -} 15. Qf3 Qc7 16. Qxa8 $2 Nc6 17. Qxf8+ Bxf8 18. Nf3 d5 $17 {
Black's powerful centre gives him an advantage. In this position, there are no
open files for the white rooks.}) 15... Nc6 16. Rad1 d6 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6,
Ga7a5] Black has no problems in this structure. He can follow with standard
moves such as ...Qb6 and ...a7-a5. In some cases, he can even consider central
expansion by means of ...f6-f5 and ...e6-e5.} *

