1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bd2
Bf6 9. Rc1 c5 10. d5 {We have already dealt with the Benoni structures. Now,
it's time to prove the theoretical soundness of Black's concept. Before
examining the Benoni type of positions, we shall take a look at some of
White's alternatives.} ({The most precise reaction to} 10. Bf4 {is} Nxc3 11.
bxc3 d6 $132 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gf8d8,Gb8c6] Black has an easy play due to his
favourable pawn structure. In the next moves, he will follow with simple moves
such as ...Qc7, ...Rd8, and possibly ...Nc6-a5. On the other hand, White does
not have constructive ideas.}) ({As we already know, the structure arising
after} 10. dxc5 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 bxc5 {is favourable for Black. It goes without
saying that we should always check whether White can pose concrete problems -}
12. Rfd1 a6 {[%cal Gf6e7,Gd7d6,Gd8c7] Black is planning to stabilize the
position with ...Qc7, ...Be7, and ...d7-d6.} 13. e4 {White is planning to gain
even more space by means of the advance e4-e5.} ({An important alternative is} 
13. Qf4 {when Black should just follow his agenda with} Be7 14. Rc2 ({Another
characteristic variaiton is} 14. Ne4 {when Black's thematic reaction is} Ra7 {
In this structure, the rook is very well placed on the 7th rank. The rook not
only moves out of the range of the white bishop but also often protects the
d7-pawn. The following variation is quite instructive.} 15. Nd6 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 (
{Obviously, after} 16. Bxf3 $4 Bg5 $19 {White loses an exchange.}) 16... Nc6
17. Qd3 Qc7 {The d6-knight is unstable. White should already reckon with ideas
like ...Ne5 and ...Nb4. Therefore, the most logical follow-up seems to be} 18.
Bxc6 Qxc6 {I would like to mention that the heavy piece endgame arising after}
19. Rc2 Bxd6 20. Qxd6 Qxd6 21. Rxd6 {is typically favourable for Black. As we
know, in this structure, the semi-open b-file gives Black a lot of active
possibilities. A typical line would be} Rb8 22. e4 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Fixing the
b2-pawn by means of ...a6-a5-a4 is a typical idea in this structure.} 23. Rdd2
Kf8 24. f4 Ke7 25. Kf2 a4 $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 14... Ra7 {
Black follows his usual strategy.} 15. Rcd2 d6 {White does not have an easy
way to put pressure on d6. A possible continuation would be} 16. Ne4 Bxe4 17.
Qxe4 Qa5 18. b3 Qb6 19. Qe3 Nd7 $11 {with equality. 1/2 (26) Hueser, U (2088)
-Raessler,A (2200) ICCF email 2012}) 13... Qc7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd7d6] An
important move. Besides preventing the advance e4-e5, Black is planning to
proceed with ...Rd8 and ...d7-d6.} 14. Qd6 {White hopes to use Black's shaky
centre in a queenless middlegame. It turns out, however, that Black holds the
structure without efforts.} Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Be7 16. Rd3 ({Harmless is} 16. Rb6 {
in view of} Ra7) 16... Ra7 {[%cal Gb7a8,Gf8d8,Gb8c6] Again and again we see
this thematic move. With a rook on a7, Black can even consider keeping the
pawn on f7 for longer. Now, he is planning to complete the development by
means of ...Ba8 followed by ...Rd8, and ...Nc6.} ({The immediate} 16... d6 $6 {
is slightly dubious since the endgame arising after} 17. e5 dxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxg2
19. Kxg2 Ra7 20. Rcd1 {is slightly better for White. Black still faces
problems related to the development of his knight.}) 17. e5 f6 $1 {Remember
this way of attacking the e5-pawn.} 18. Rcd1 Rd8 19. exf6 gxf6 $132 {Black's
good central control and bishop pair provide enough counterplay. 1/2 (23)
Tasic, V-Fichtner,B (2370) ICCF 2010}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 {
[%cal Gd2e4] The most ambitious continuation. White is planning to proceed
with Nde4 followed by the advance of his kingside pawns.} ({After} 12. Qxd2 d6
13. Ne4 Be7 14. Rfd1 Nd7 $132 {Black enjoys a decent Benoni structure. He can
already think of the advance ...b6-b5.}) 12... d6 13. Nde4 {The most
principled continuation.} ({The alternative} 13. a4 {is less challenging. In
this case, my suggestion would be} Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4] The knight is immediately
heading for the weakened b4-square.} 14. Nc4 Nb4 15. Nb5 Be7 16. Qd2 Re8 17.
Rfd1 {[%cal Gd2f4] Black should already go for concrete play since White is
planning to increase the pressure on d6 by means of Qf4.} Ba6 {[%cal Ga6b5] We
know that in Benoni structures, Black gladly gets rid of his light-squared
bishop.} ({An alternative solution would be} 17... a6 18. Nd4 Rc8 19. Nf5 b5
20. Nxe7+ Rxe7 $132 {with decent counterplay.}) 18. e4 (18. Nd4 $2 Bg5) 18...
Bxb5 19. axb5 Bf6 $132 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 13... Be5 {This is
the most active continuation.} ({Of course} 13... Be7 {is a decent alternative.
}) 14. f4 {White starts his kingside expansion without further preparation.} ({
More cautious is} 14. Qd2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge5d4,Ge2e3] The idea is to follow with
f2-f4 on the next move. By taking the e3-square under control, White is ready
to answer ...Bd4+ with e2-e3. Therefore, Black should play} Ba6 $1 {activating
the light-squared bishop and pinning the e2-pawn.} 15. Rfe1 {This move
indicates White's intention to play in the centre.} ({An important alternative
is} 15. f4 Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Qe7 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 17. Rf3 Nd7 18. g4 {A typical idea
in this line. Black's most natural reaction is} Rfe8 {putting pressure on the
e-file. If White starts wasting time, Black is ready to follow with ...
b6-b5-b4. It's important to remember that in case of} 19. e3 {the thematic
reaction is} Bxc3 20. Nxc3 c4 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5] followed by ...Nc5. Black
immediately makes use of the newly weakened d3-square.}) 15... g6 {[%cal Ge5g7]
freeing the g7-square for the bishop.} 16. f4 Bg7 17. a4 {Before starting his
play in the centre and on the kingside, White's wants to prevent Black's
queenside counterplay.} Qe7 18. Ng5 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ge4e5] Planning to follow
with e2-e4-e5.} ({After having played Rfe1, the idea} 18. g4 Nd7 19. g5 {
looks less impressive. In my opinion, Black should play} c4 {[%cal Gd7c5] with
the idea of ...Nc5. Critical seems to be} 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. axb5 Rac8 22. e3 Nc5
23. Rxc4 Nxe4 24. Rxe4 Qd7 $44 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gf8c8] Black is ready to double
his rooks on the c-file. He has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 18... Nd7
19. e4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Nf6 21. e5 {The most critical test.} ({The move} 21. Nf3 {
was met in the game 1/2 (21) Ionov, S (2500) -Yemelin, V (2380) Orel 1992. At
this point, Black should have played} Bxc3 22. Rxc3 Nxe4 {The following moves
are quite logical -} 23. Qc1 Bb7 24. Ng5 f5 25. Rce3 Qf6 26. Nxe4 fxe4 27. Qd2
Rae8 28. Bxe4 Re7 {Black does not face any problems.}) 21... dxe5 22. Nf3 Bxc3
23. bxc3 e4 24. Ne5 Qd6 25. c4 {Obviously, White is going to regain the pawn.
On the other hand, Black's position remains quite sensible.} Rfe8 26. Qc2 Bc8
27. Bxe4 Nxe4 28. Qxe4 Bd7 $132 {Black enjoys decent counterplay.}) 14... Bd4+
15. Kh1 Ba6 16. Rf3 {This is by far the most principled approach. Black's next
moves are quite familiar to us -} Re8 17. g4 Qe7 18. g5 Nd7 19. e3 {As always,
the typical reaction to this advance is} Bxc3 20. Nxc3 c4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal
Gd7c5]} ({That said, fighting against White's space advantage with} 20... f6 {
is possible as well. For instance, after} 21. Bh3 fxg5 22. Qa4 Bc8 23. Rg1 Nf6
$132 {Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 21. Rh3 {[%cal Gd1h5]} f5 $1 {
A typical way of neutralizing White's space advantage on the kingside.} (21...
b5 22. Qh5 $36) 22. Ne2 ({After} 22. gxf6 Nxf6 $132 {[%cal Ga6c8,Gc8f5] Black
has enough conterplay. White should reckon with the maneuver ...Bc8-f5.}) 22...
Nc5 23. Nd4 Nd3 $132 {Black has good dynamic potential in this position. He
can proceed with ...Qf7 followed by ...Bb7, thus targetting the d5-pawn.} *

