{Black to move} 12... Qd7 $1 {In this structure, it's very important to answer
e2-e4 with ...fxe4 followed by ...d6-d5. That's why Black protects the e6-pawn
in advance. Additionally, with his last move, Black prepares ...Nc6.} 13. b3 {
[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1d1] White does not rush. Before going for e2-e4, he wants to
mobilize his forces by means of Bb2 followed by Rad1. Since Black has already
played ...f7-f5, his best strategy is to prepare ...e6-e5 with ...Bf6 and ...
Nc6. Remember that the move ...f7-f5 almost never goes along with ...c7-c5. In
such a case, when the tension is released, Black will find himself with shaky
central pawns. He would very much like to play the illegal ...f5-f7 move!} Bf6
14. Bb2 Nc6 15. Rad1 Rae8 {Black has achieved his classical setup. He is
getting ready for the advance ...e6-e5. Finally, White went for} 16. e4 {
Probably, the reader would remember that Black should answer this move with}
fxe4 17. Qxe4 d5 {Suddenly, it transpires that White should take care of his
d4-pawn.} *

