{Black to move} 15... Ne4 {[%cal Gf7f6] It turns out that the e5-knight is not
threatening at all. Black is ready to follow with ...f7-f6.} 16. Bxe4 {Sooner
or later White opts for this move since it's impossible to live with the
e4-knight for too long. With his last move, White also frees the c4-square for
the knight.} ({Nothing changes after} 16. Qh5 f6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nc4 a5 {
when it's very likely that we will get the same type of opposite-coloured
bishops middlegame, as in the game. In this concrete case, Black has the
additional possibility of ...a5-a4.}) 16... dxe4 17. Nc4 Bd5 $1 {This is a key
move in Black's concept. Black already anticipates the middlegame with
opposite coloured bishops. By blocking the d4-pawn, Kryvoruchko prevents his
opponent from activating the bishop by means of d4-d5. Additionally, with a
bishop on d5, Black can already play ...c7-c6, eliminating White's pressure on
the c-file.} 18. Nxd6 $6 {This move makes Black's advantage even bigger. On
the other hand, suggesting a constructive idea for White is far from easy.}
Qxd6 $17 {The arising middlegame with opposite-coloured bishops is clearly
better for Black. In such middlegames, the possibility to organize a kingside
attack is what matters. The e4-pawn provides a lot of space on the kingside.} *

