{Black to move} 10... Nc6 $1 {This is the key move. It turns out that White
cannot simultaneously take care of the d4-pawn and cover the e4-square. The
main drawback is the vulnerable d4-pawn.} 11. Qf3 {This thematic move is
designed to take the e4-square under control. Additionally, in some cases, the
queen can be transferred to g3 or h3.} ({The attempt to protect the d4-pawn by
means of} 11. Ne2 {is well met by} Ne4 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] when White does not
have any attacking chances. Black can chase the e5-knight away whenever he
wants. Meanwhile, Black is ready to expand on the queenside by means of ...
a7-a5-a4. In this case, the idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops via
a6 is always on the agenda.}) 11... cxd4 {Black immediately uses the drawback
of White's last move. In order not to lose a pawn, White is forced to part
with the pride of his position - the e5-knight. Jussupow played} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6
13. exd4 Re8 {The position has stabilized and we can already draw some
concrete conclusions. Had White the possibility to make an illegal move, his
choice would have been f4-f2! Fighting for the e4-square is Black's main
positional idea. It goes without saying that after exchanging the
light-squared bishops, he wants to install a knight on e4. A possible idea is .
..Qd7 followed by ...b6-b5-b4. After kicking the knight back, Black can
exchange the light-squared bishops via b5.} *

