25. Qf5 $2 {This move is already a decisive mistake.} ({More logical would
have been} 25. Ne5 {When playing against hanging pawns, we try to exchange
pieces. A possible continuation would be} Nxe5 26. Bxe5 Qe6 27. Bxf6 Bxf6 28.
Qc2 a5 $132 {The advance ...a6-a5 is always useful in such positions. Besides
gaining queenside space, Black rules out any b3-b4 ideas. The position remains
balanced.}) 25... d4 $1 {Black delivers this thematic break under perfect
circumstances.} 26. exd4 cxd4 {[%csl Rc3] We can now see the point behind 21...
Rb8. The entire operation works due to the vulnerable c3-knight.} 27. Na4 d3 $1
{One more important move. The d3-pawn is untouchable due to the backrank
weakness.} *

